# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] The **GM 10.5" 14-bolt differential** stands as a robust drivetrain component extensively featured in Chevrolet and GMC trucks, SUVs, and vans from 1973 onward, including specific versions of the Cadillac Escalade.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] Introduced in 1973, this differential employs a full-floating design, boasting a substantial ring gear diameter measuring 10.5 inches (270 mm).
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] Its nomenclature, "14-bolt," represents the 14 bolts securing the differential cover, although the ring gear itself is fastened by 12 bolts.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] Notably, the 14-bolt differential gained traction among Jeep Wrangler owners seeking axle replacement options, earning the moniker "corporate" 14-bolt because of its association with GM's corporate structure during the 1970s.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] Distinguishing it from the GM 14-bolt 9.5-inch ring gear rear differential is the latter's utilization of C-clips to retain axles, differing from the free-floating axle mechanism of its heavy-duty counterpart.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] Identification between the two can be made by examining the hub: the protrusion of the hub through the center of the wheel denotes the preferred 10.5-inch full-floating rear axle.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] While the 9.5-inch rear end exhibits its own durability, it is generally considered less favorable for high-torque applications.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] The 9.5-inch C-clip rear differential was featured in both the Suburban and pickups, available in 6- or 8-lug variations, employing 33-spline axles.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] This differential remained in production through 2009 and even found use in vehicles like the TrailBlazer SS, Saab 9-7X, and SSR.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] The initial design of the GM 10.5" 14-bolt differential spanned from 1973 to 1984, remaining unaltered until 1986.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] This iteration featured brake drums secured by wheel studs and utilized a smaller diameter pinion bearing compared to the subsequent design.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] The second design, in production since 1986, introduced notable improvements.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] Some models allowed for the removal of the brake drum without requiring hub and axle shaft removal.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] Additionally, a larger diameter bearing enhanced the durability of the pinion while maintaining its original diameter.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] Notably, both designs employed a full-floating axle system, bolstering their robustness.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] Braking systems in the 14-bolt differentials manufactured until the 1998 model year predominantly incorporated drum brakes.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] However, select 1999 models with the 14-bolt configuration received upgrades to disc brakes; for example, the new Silverado/Sierra 2500 trucks.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] Full-size GM vans continued featuring drum brakes for several more years, transitioning entirely to disc brakes by 2003.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] The original design of the braking system within the 14-bolt differentials accommodated diverse wheel sizes, initially fitting drums suitable for 15-inch wheels and later adapting to cater to the needs of 3/4-ton and 1-ton vehicles.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] Enthusiasts often opt to convert this section of the axle assembly to disc brakes for enhanced performance and reduced maintenance costs.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] The pinion is supported both in front of and behind the pinion teeth, an arrangement often referred to as "straddle mounting." Straddle mounting greatly reduces pinion deflection under high torque loads, conferring increased longevity and torque capacity.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] The pinion is also removable from the back as well, making for easier access.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] The 10.5" 14-bolt differential and axle is quite popular with Jeep Wrangler owners who want to upgrade their standard Dana 30, Dana 35, or Dana 44 axle.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] While the 10.5" 14-bolt axle is heavier than the standard Dana axles offered on the Wrangler, it is much stronger.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] This increased strength allows Jeep Wrangler owners to mount up to 44" tires with sticky compound without concern about axle shaft breakage.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] Additionally, for Wrangler owners with high-horsepower GM LS engines, the 14-bolt can handle the engines' increased stress.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] Many Wrangler owners will have up to two inches removed from the bottom of the 10.5" 14-bolt differential housing to maximize ground clearance.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] The popularity of GM trucks and vans made 10.5" 14-bolt axles a common sight in junkyards, making them an option for vehicle customization projects, including buggy builds and even classic trucks.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] The 11.5 AAM 14-bolt rear differential started replacing the 10.5" 14-bolt in Chevrolet Silverado and GMC Sierra trucks from the 2001 model year onwards.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] However, the 10.5" 14-bolt axle remains in production today, specifically utilized in GMC Savana and Chevrolet Express vans.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] Notably, the 11.5" 14-bolt axle is featured in third-generation Dodge Ram 2500 and 3500 trucks.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] There are discernible differences between the GM and Ram versions, evident in the gaskets used and the axle cover designs.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] The GM AAM axle tubes exhibit a smaller diameter at the spindle compared to the AAM Dodge axles—measuring 4" for GM and 3.5" for Dodge from the housing.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] In design variation, newer GM trucks are aligned with Dodge axles.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] Additionally, GM incorporates a vibration damper on the yoke, while Dodge positions it on the drive shaft.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] This configuration became the standard axle across all Ram 2500 and 3500 trucks starting from the 2014 model year.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] In third-generation Dodge Ram 2500 trucks, the 10.5 AAM axle was used in all V8-equipped trucks, with some early-model diesel and V10 trucks also adopting this axle.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] Similar to the 11.5 variant, this axle also features a reusable rubber gasket and bears a resemblance to the 11.5 axle in its appearance.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] Notably, the Ram Power Wagon incorporates this axle type equipped with a locking differential.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/10-5-corporate-14-bolt-differential] The 2013 model year marked the final usage of this axle configuration in the Ram 2500 and 3500 trucks.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] The **2007 General Motors Strike** was a labor union strike that lasted three days from September 23 to September 25, 2007, organized by the United Auto Workers (UAW) union.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] The UAW were engaged in talks with General Motors (GM) to negotiate a new labor contract but were unable to come to an agreement before the deadline.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] Consequently, 73,000 workers walked out forcing 80 GM facilities in 30 states to cease operations.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] After the two day strike, the two parties reached an agreement in which the UAW union would assume the responsibility for managing retiree healthcare liabilities.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] The UAW previously went on strike against General Motors in 1970.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] The automobile industry landscape in 2007 was drastically different to what it once was.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] GM's market share had been steadily decreasing as foreign automakers entered the market.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] Foreign players secured over 50% of market share for the first time in history in July 2007.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] GM's foreign competitors Nissan, Honda, and Toyota increased their production within the United States.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] Part of GM's struggles has been its relatively high costs of production.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] While many of the foreign manufacturers pay less in wages as most of their plants are not a part of a union, GM's labor contracts increase its costs per car by an estimated $2000 impacting its competitiveness.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] These costs can be attributed to worker pensions and healthcare programs the unions have negotiated.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] The number of UAW members at GM has also steadily decreased as the company downsized.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] At the time of the 2007 strike, the 73,000 workers at GM are far lower than the 400,000 workers GM employed when the UAW last went on strike in 1970.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] The UAW's lower overall membership was also caused by the increasing prevalence of non-unionized plants and factories belonging to foreign automakers.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] It once had over 1.5 million workers but by 2007, that number had shrunk to just several hundred thousand.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] General Motors' previous labor contract with the UAW union went up until September 14, 2007.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] Both parties agreed to an extension of 10 days until September 24 as the UAW felt that negotiations were still progressing.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] However, following the end of this 10 day period, as negotiations came to a stalemate the UAW believed a strike was necessary as GM refused to acquiesce to the UAW's demands in regards to job security and worker benefits.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] General Motors' losing market share within the United States automobile market has forced the company to downsize the company.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] In the two years leading up to 2007, GM had incurred $12.3 billion in losses.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] In response, GM has since closed down numerous factories and laid off thousands of workers.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] At the time of the strike, GM was also planning on cutting an additional 30,000 jobs in the coming year.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] The UAW wanted to ensure job security for the remaining GM workers and demanded for guarantees stipulating that those workers employed under the contract would stay employed until the contract expired.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] Another issue of contention between GM and UAW was the company's liabilities to retirees in regards to their healthcare benefits.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] These liabilities amounted to $51 billion.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] Both parties were in talks to discuss transferring these liabilities to a trust, which was GM's primary demand.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] The establishment of a voluntary employee benefit association (VEBA) has been an idea that was widely embraced by GM's investors and managers.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] Doing so what entail a large initial payment from GM but would allow it to remove workers healthcare benefits as a liability on its balance sheet.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] It was believed that removing these costs from the equation would allow GM to increase its competitiveness in the industry.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] Immediately after the deadline had passed, the UAW union moved to a national strike that involved 73,000 workers walking out of an estimated 80 GM facilities.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] After the union announced the strike, negotiations continued that same afternoon lasting over five hours.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] In the UAW's press conference, its president Ron Gettelfinger expressed his disappointment in GM's management and their refusal to meet the union halfway.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] He believed that the UAW had no choice but to strike stating that: “There comes a point in time where you have to draw a line in the sand”.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] Many saw this as the UAW refusing to roll over to management's demands from GM.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] Gettelfinger also expressed that the UAW was willing to consider GM's request to form a trust to take on healthcare liabilities, and that job security remained the union's number one concern.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] The effect of the strike was an operational halt that would otherwise produce 12,200 cars a day.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] Concerns were raised regarding the effect of the strike on GM if an agreement wasn't reached.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] The strike had the potential to influence GM supply chains and overseas plants that manufacture parts.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] Nearby operations in Mexico and Canada would also suffer as a result.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] The strike became a focus within the automobile industry as how it played it out would likely affect negotiations the UAW would later have with Ford and Chrysler given the vulnerable state of the United States’ auto companies.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] Despite the strike, Michael Robinet, the vice president of CSM Worldwide and an expert on global vehicle forecasts, predicted that GM would not have any issues with a shortage of vehicle production.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] In fact, he expected that the company would not experience issues related to inventory shortages for two to three weeks should the strike continue as a result of no agreement being reached.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] At the time, GM's inventory levels were generally higher than that of their competitors, a point that many linked to the company's poor sales in recent months leading up to the strike.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] On the first day of the strike, GM's stock closed 20 cents lower in the trading session, wiping out what was originally a gain of 2.6% earlier on in the day.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] The consensus amongst analysts evaluating GM's position in the strike was that while a long strike would be highly detrimental for the company as it seeks to turn its business around and become more profitable.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] With that said, many believed that GM would still be well positioned to endure a strike that was shorter in nature.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] On September 26, it was announced that early that morning, the UAW and GM reached a deal.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] Specifics of the deal were not made available, however the headline for GM was that the UAW had agreed to the establishment of a VEBA that would assume the retiree healthcare liabilities worth $51 billion.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] Gettelfinger described that job guarantees were made by GM although the details were not disclosed.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] After reaching the deal, the UAW's executives stated their intention to meet again on the 28th of September to discuss and approve the contract.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] If successful, the contract would then be moved to be voted on by the workers in the union to finalize the agreement.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] Gettelfinger expressed his confidence that GM's workers would vote in favor of this newly negotiated contract.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] Had the contract not been approved by both the UAW leaders and the workers, the UAW made it clear that the strike would continue.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] It was reported that members who had information regarding the details of the VEBA disclosed that the trust would be funded by a combination of various assets including cash and GM stock.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] The trust's establishment would be subject to approval by the Security and Exchange Commission and the relevant court of law.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] The approval process was expected to last over a year with the earliest completion date being sometime in 2009.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] The agreement involved allowing GM to access the pension fund for the purpose of reimbursing retirees for the increased healthcare benefits offered in the years preceding the deal, as the pension was seen as being overfunded.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] Newspapers also reported sources that indicated some of the terms of the new contract involved a steep decrease in the wages of lower tier workers along with lower signing bonuses.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] Other sources confirmed that the two parties agreed to meet on a yearly basis to evaluate and discuss the healthcare trust.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] It was reported that GM was willing to make additional contributions to the fund if it was determined to be necessary if the amount was within a range the company considered reasonable.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] It was also expected that the leaders of the UAW would discuss the details of the GM contract with labor officials at the other large automobile manufacturers, Ford and Chrysler, as a part of a series of labor contract negotiations within the industry.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] At the time, the UAW union was also in negotiations with them over new labor contracts although little progress had been made.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] Many experts pointed out the possibility that both Ford and Chrysler could establish similar VEBA trusts which would reduce liabilities, something that many of these companies have looked forward to.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] GM believed that the agreement would allow them to "significantly improve its manufacturing competitiveness".
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] Investor sentiment regarding the deal being reached was generally positive for GM as they have been proponents for the establishment of the VEBA trust.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] After the deal was reached between GM and the UAW union, the stock price of GM increased by 4.2% in the morning of that trading session, and closed with a 9% rise reaching its highest mark in ten weeks.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] GM's bond prices also increased following the news.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] The stock price of Ford increased by more than 6% in the same session, likely linked to investor expectations that a similar deal would be reached in their negotiations with the UAW.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] Credit rating agencies shared a similarly positive response to the deal.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] Fitch was in discussions to lower GM's rating and that of some of its suppliers, however decided to hold off after the new deal was announced.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] Standard and Poor’s discussed the possibility of increasing GM's long term rating moving forward.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] GM pointed out their healthcare spending in the previous year totaled $4.8 billion, an amount that could have been spent towards launching six vehicle models or building an additional four manufacturing plants.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2007-general-motors-strike] Wall street analysts were expecting GM to benefit from increased healthcare cost savings amounting to $3 billion annually as a consequence of the newly established VEBA trust.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2019-general-motors-strike] The **2019 General Motors strike** began September 15, 2019, with the walkout of 48,000 United Automobile Workers from some 50 plants in the United States.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2019-general-motors-strike] Demands by workers included increased job security, gateway for temporary workers to become permanent, better pay and retaining healthcare benefits.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2019-general-motors-strike] The strike lasted six weeks, and ended when GM conceded to union demands on wage growth and health care costs because the new contract allows GM to close three factories: the Lordstown Assembly plant, the Baltimore Transmission plant, and the Warren Transmission plant.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2019-general-motors-strike] This strike constituted the first major labor action in the American automotive industry in a decade.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2019-general-motors-strike] The last strike coordinated by the UAW targeting General Motors occurred in 2007.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2019-general-motors-strike] During the Great Recession and economic uncertainty that followed, unionized automotive workers accepted concessions to allow GM and other companies to recover.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2019-general-motors-strike] Though GM has since received large tax breaks and returned to profitability, worker compensation remained stagnant, and the UAW took umbrage with the company's decisions to shutter American facilities and move some jobs abroad.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2019-general-motors-strike] The contract between the UAW and General Motors expired September 14, and the strike began at 11:59 p.m. on September 15, 2019.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2019-general-motors-strike] A two-day difference between contract expiration and the beginning of a strike is unusually short, but likely motivated by the prolonged negotiations between management and the union.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2019-general-motors-strike] The strike involved 48,000 GM employees.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2019-general-motors-strike] On September 17, GM stopped providing health insurance to 55,000 union members, forcing the UAW to pay for COBRA.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2019-general-motors-strike] On September 26, it was announced that GM would start to pay health insurance again to people on strike.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2019-general-motors-strike] On October 16, it was announced that GM and the UAW agreed on a new labor contract that ended the month-long strike.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2019-general-motors-strike] However, the agreement between GM and UAW had not been officially approved, and workers who were still on strike said that they would wait until the deal had been ratified before they returned to their jobs.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2019-general-motors-strike] The new contract was ratified by UAW members on October 25, ending the strike.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2019-general-motors-strike] The strike lasted six weeks, and ended when GM conceded to union demands on wage growth and healthcare costs because the new contract allowed GM to close three factories: the Lordstown plant, the Baltimore plant, and a transmission plant in Warren.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2019-general-motors-strike] An analyst for Credit Suisse estimated that GM could lose as much as $50 million each day the strike continued, while other analysts estimated daily losses could be as high as $100 million per day.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2019-general-motors-strike] GM's share of the automobile market had decreased from 30% in the late 1990s to 17% by 2019, meaning the strike likely had fewer implications for the economy at large when compared to labor actions in the past.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2019-general-motors-strike] The strike was also predicted to possibly lead to impacts on GM factories abroad, which rely on parts produced in American factories closed because of the strike, and on suppliers such as Canada-based Magna International.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2019-general-motors-strike] At the beginning of the strike, GM had roughly 83 days' worth of inventory available for sale, temporarily insulating its supply chain from the impact of the strike.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2019-general-motors-strike] The Teamsters refused to deliver GM cars during the strike, in solidarity with GM workers.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2019-general-motors-strike] Members of the Trump administration, including Larry Kudlow and Peter Navarro, allegedly intervened in negotiations; however, GM and the White House have both denied Kudlow and Navarro's involvement.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2019-general-motors-strike] On September 21, Senator Elizabeth Warren, running at the time for the Democratic nomination for President of the United States, joined a UAW picket line in Detroit.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/2019-general-motors-strike] Other Democratic contenders for the nomination including Senator Bernie Sanders, former vice-president Joe Biden, Senator Amy Klobuchar, and Representative Tim Ryan, also visited picket lines during the strike.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The portion of the building at the corner of 57th Street and Broadway was built for car manufacturer Aaron T.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The section belonging to the former Peerless Motor Company is an L-shaped structure wrapping around the A.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] 224 West 57th Street is 11 stories tall; the former Demarest section rises nine stories, while the Peerless section contains a partial tenth floor and an additional two-story tower.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] 224 West 57th Street contains a steel-frame curtain wall, concrete piers, and a facade of glazed architectural terracotta.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Inside, both of the former structures had automotive storerooms at ground level and warehouses and repair facilities on the upper floors.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The Demarest and Peerless buildings were constructed simultaneously in 1909.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] General Motors (GM) bought both buildings in 1918 and combined them internally.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] After GM constructed other buildings in Manhattan, 224 West 57th Street was renamed the Argonaut Building to avoid confusion.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The Hearst Corporation bought 224 West 57th Street in 1977 and housed its Hearst Magazine department there until 2006.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission designated the building as a city landmark in 2000.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The building was renovated from 2008 to 2011 and subsequently became the headquarters of Open Society Foundations.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] 224 West 57th Street is on the southeastern corner of Broadway and 57th Street, two blocks south of Columbus Circle and Central Park in the Midtown Manhattan neighborhood of New York City.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The building carries the addresses 1758–1770 Broadway and 224–228 West 57th Street.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The lot occupies an area of 14,200 feet (4,300 m), with frontage of 136 feet (41 m) on Broadway and 141 feet (43 m) on 57th Street.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The lot measures 116 feet (35 m) along its eastern lot line and 91.6 feet (27.9 m) on its southern lot line.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] 224 West 57th Street abuts the American Society of Civil Engineers' Society House to the east and faces Central Park Tower to the north.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Other nearby buildings include the American Fine Arts Society (also known as the Art Students League of New York building) and Osborne Apartments to the northeast; Rodin Studios and 888 Seventh Avenue to the east; and 1740 Broadway to the south.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] In the 20th century, the area was part of Manhattan's "Automobile Row", a stretch of Broadway extending mainly between Times Square at 42nd Street and Sherman Square at 72nd Street.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Before the first decade of the 20th century, the area was occupied mostly by equestrian industries and was described by *The New York Times* as "thoroughly lifeless".
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] By 1907, the *Times* characterized this section of Broadway as having "almost a solid line of motor vehicle signs all the way from Times Square to Sherman Square".
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] In the late 1900s and early 1910s, several large automobile showrooms, stores, and garages were built on Broadway, including the B.F.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Goodrich showroom (later part of Central Park Tower) and the U.S.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Rubber Company Building just north of 224 West 57th Street.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Both of the formerly separate buildings comprising 224 West 57th Street, the Demarest and Peerless Buildings, were designed by Francis H.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The Demarest Company section takes up the corner lot, measuring 66 by 116 feet (20 by 35 m), while the Peerless Company section occupies an L-shaped lot around the Demarest Building and measures 70 feet (21 m) wide on Broadway by 25 feet (7.6 m) wide on 57th Street.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The structure was erected by the George A.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Fuller Company with Purdy and Henderson as the consulting engineer.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The design of 224 West 57th Street's constituent structures incorporates many Gothic Revival and Romanesque Revival architectural details, to complement each other and the now-demolished Broadway Tabernacle church building to the south.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Most of 224 West 57th Street is nine stories tall, although there is a tenth story atop part of the building.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] 224 West 57th Street's eastern section, belonging to the former Peerless Building, contains a penthouse rising two additional stories above the main roof.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] In total, 224 West 57th Street is 12 stories tall and has a roof height of 132.91 feet (40.51 m).
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The facade, made almost entirely of terracotta, contains many decorative elements created by the New York Architectural Terra-Cotta Company.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The northern and western elevations or sides of 224 West 57th Street are both subdivided into five groupings, each with three bays, and are connected by a canted corner.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The northern two groupings on Broadway and the western four groupings on 57th Street belonged to the Demarest Building, while the southern three groupings on Broadway and the easternmost grouping on 57th Street was part of the Peerless Building.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The southern facade, was originally visible behind the nave of the Broadway Tabernacle.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] At the first and second stories, each of the five triple-width groupings are subdivided by double-height pilasters with cartouches at their tops.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] As built, these wide groupings originally contained automotive storefronts or entrances for pedestrians or vehicles.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The easternmost grouping on 57th Street has a glass-and-metal doorway under a transom, and is flanked by inscribed bronze plaques with the building's name and address.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The corner entrance at Broadway and 57th Street has glass-and-metal door under a transom.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The facade has various ornamentation on the third through ninth stories, including colonettes, arched windows, cornices, and brackets.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The second-southernmost grouping of the Broadway elevation has an oriel window spanning the fifth through seventh floors.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Above the ninth floor, there are pediments over the six groupings comprising the former Demarest Building, and parapets over the four groupings that make up the former Peerless Building.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The southern elevation is clad in terracotta, but because of the presence of a neighboring building, only the westernmost two bays of the southern elevation are visible.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The eastern elevation is made largely of tan brick.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The two-story penthouse above the Peerless Building's easternmost section is clad in tan brick and contains terracotta trim, quoined pilasters, round arches with keyed surrounds, and tile signs on the western elevation.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] There were formerly also tile signs on the eastern and northern elevations of the penthouse.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] 224 West 57th Street has 164,000 square feet (15,200 m2) of usable interior space.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] This includes 6,000 square feet (560 m2) at ground level, 4,800 square feet (450 m2) in the tenth-floor penthouse, and between 10,000 and 18,000 square feet (930 and 1,670 m2) on each of the other floors.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Both constituent structures are supported by an internal steel frame atop concrete foundation piers, with the facade acting as a curtain wall.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Upon completion, the corner Demarest Building had offices as well as carriage and automobile warehouses.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] There was one elevator each for pedestrians and vehicles.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The surrounding Peerless Building had a double-height ground-floor salesroom, with a gilded ceiling and marble walls and columns.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The second through tenth floors respectively contained vehicle stock, new cars, used cars, an inspection studio, an upholstery department, repair shops, more repair shops, a painting department, and a blacksmith shop.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The Peerless Building had two vehicle elevators, one passenger elevator, and a turntable.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Realty, a company associated with builder George A.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Fuller, purchased five lots at the southeast corner of 57th Street and Broadway in 1902.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The lots had come under the ownership of Robert E.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Dowling by 1905, when Dowling transferred these lots to the Island Realty Company.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Island Realty planned to build an apartment hotel on the site, although this ultimately did not happen.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The easternmost section of the lot was sold to the American Society of Civil Engineers in 1905 to make room for an extension of their Society House.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The Peerless and Demarest companies were among the companies that moved to Automobile Row in the first decade of the 20th century.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The Peerless Motor Car Company of New York, a subsidiary of the Peerless Motor Company of Cleveland, Ohio, was headquartered at 220 West 41st Street by 1905.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Demarest, was headquartered on Fifth Avenue and 33rd Street prior to the construction of its 57th Street showroom.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] By December 1908, the Demarest Company leased the three corner lots at Broadway and 57th Street, intending to build a showroom and shop there.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] That month, Kimball was hired to prepare plans for a pair of buildings to be occupied by the Peerless and Demarest companies.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Doan Realty, a subsidiary of the Peerless Company, bought the two lots surrounding the Demarest Company's land by mid-1909.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Realty also sold off the corner plots under the new Demarest Building to the Matoaka Realty Company.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Construction on the buildings commenced in March 1909.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The Demarest Company's building was completed by that June, while the Peerless Company's building was completed three months later in September.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The Peerless Building represented an investment of $1 million, and collectively employed 250 workers upon completion.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Peerless wrote that the new building allowed them to modify, repair, upholster, paint, and store cars "under one roof", and the word "Peerless" was mounted on the northern face of the Peerless Building's tower.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] One of the Peerless Building's two vehicle elevators was removed in 1912.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Both the Demarest and Peerless companies stayed in their respective showrooms for less than a decade after their completion.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Peerless had moved out by 1915, and Demarest stopped leasing its showroom by 1917.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The Chevrolet Company, the automotive division of General Motors (GM), leased the Demarest Building starting in May 1917, and hired Henry Janeway Hardenbergh to renovate the Demarest Building.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The following October, Chevrolet bought the Peerless and Demarest buildings at a combined $1.5 million.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Sources vary on the sequence of the subsequent renovation.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission (LPC) and the *Real Estate Record and Guide* wrote that GM hired Hardenbergh for the renovations, with plans for the existing elevators and stairs to be taken out and replaced with three passenger elevators.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] However, *The New York Times* stated that the buildings were renovated by J.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Phelan, and that while the Peerless Building's original vehicular entrance on 57th Street was removed, the Demarest Building's vehicular elevator was left intact.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] According to the *Times*, the upper floors were renovated and the blacksmiths' shop became a dining room for executives.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The two structures became known as the General Motors Building at 224 West 57th Street, and a tile sign with the words "General Motors Corporation" was added to the Peerless Building's tower.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] 224 West 57th Street thus served as General Motors' headquarters in New York City, and contained GM's general offices as well as those of Chevrolet, the General Motors Acceptance Corporation, and the General Motors Export Company.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] By 1926, GM was developing 3 Columbus Circle, a 26-story skyscraper diagonally across from 224 West 57th Street, for use as its New York City headquarters.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] GM's offices were relocated to 3 Columbus Circle in 1927, and 224 West 57th Street became known as the Argonaut Building.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] GM continued to use the Argonaut Building as a showroom, opening a Cadillac and LaSalle showroom on the ground level in 1935.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] At that point, vehicle elevators between the basement and the third floor were installed.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] According to the building's subsequent owners, the first built-in car radios were sold inside the showroom in 1938.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] During the 1940s, the Automobile Merchants Association took space in the building, as did the United States Office of War Information and the *Voice of America*.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The *Voice* and the Office of War Information had leased all of the office floors during World War II, but GM retook most of the space after the end of the war.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The second and third floors of the Argonaut Building became office space in 1964, and the ground-level showroom operated through the late 1970s.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Although General Motors completed a new headquarters and showroom building at 767 Fifth Avenue in 1968, GM stated that it would retain the Argonaut Building after the completion of the new structure.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] By the 1970s, GM had moved its divisions in the Argonaut Building to other locations.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Hearst Communications started to lease space in the Argonaut Building in 1975, and purchased the property outright two years later in July 1977.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The LPC designated 224 West 57th Street, along with the U.S.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Rubber Company Building and the Studebaker Building in Brooklyn, as official city landmarks on December 19, 2000.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The terracotta facade was repaired and painted with a white coating in 2006.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Although Christopher Gray of *The New York Times* said conservators usually disapproved of applying coating to terracotta, the facade had already been coated previously, so the modification was approved by the LPC.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Also in 2006, Hearst moved its headquarters one block west to the Hearst Tower, following the completion of that building.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] 224 West 57th Street was leased by foreign developer M1 Real Estate in 2008 for 99 years.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] At the time, Gensler was already planning to renovate the building for $45 million; the building was thus vacated, with ground-floor tenant Duane Reade moving out.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] A branch of TD Bank signed a lease for the ground floor space in 2009, and M1 purchased 224 West 57th Street from Hearst for $85 million the next year.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Gensler's renovation was completed in 2011 and received a Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design (LEED) Gold award from the U.S.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] This made 224 West 57th Street one of a few buildings over 100 years old to receive LEED Gold certification.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] George Soros's Open Society Foundations leased all the office space at the Argonaut Building in September 2011, with the former ground-floor showroom housing a bank by that time.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Tirmizi Campbell subsequently renovated the interior space for OSF's use, with the project being completed in 2013.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Eretz Group purchased 224 West 57th Street from M1 Real Estate in 2015 for $214 million, and the owners secured a $145 million loan for the building in 2018.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] By mid-2022, Open Society Foundations was still the only office tenant in the Argonaut Building.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Soros Fund Management moved to foreclose on the building's mortgage in April 2024.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] That June, the delinquent mortgages on the building were sold by Deutsche Bank and another German lender to the George Soros Family office.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] Shortly after the Peerless and Demarest buildings opened, *Architects' and Builders' Magazine* wrote that the designs complemented the Broadway Tabernacle "in a harmonious and satisfactory manner".
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] The magazine wrote that the Gothic designs differed from each other "in every detail", but "in spirit conveys the same idea".
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/224-west-57th-street] In 2007, Gray wrote in *The New York Times* that the facade, which complemented the long-demolished Broadway Tabernacle, "seems a bit out of place amid the traffic at one of the busiest intersections in Midtown".
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] United Motors Corporation was formed by William C.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] Durant in 1916 as an automotive component and accessory holding company.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] Durant was the owner of Buick and founder of General Motors in 1908.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] After he lost control of General Motors in 1910, he founded Chevrolet in 1911 with Louis Chevrolet and the profits from this permitted him to regain control of GM in 1916.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] At approximately the same time, he assembled United Motors.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] Durant's founding of United Motors has parallels in his earlier experience in the horse-drawn carriage industry in Michigan.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] In the late 19th century he was co-owner of the Durant-Dort Carriage Company, one of the nation's leading carriage manufacturers.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] Concerned that they could not source components and raw materials at affordable prices or in sufficient quantities, Durant-Dort created a vertically-integrated operation owning hardwood forests and manufacturing its own bodies, wheels, axles, upholstery, springs, varnish and whips.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] United Motors initially included Alfred P.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] Sloan's Hyatt Roller Bearing Company (antifriction roller bearings), New Departure Manufacturing Company (ball bearings), Remy Electric Company (electrical starting, lighting, and ignition equipment), Charles Kettering and Edward A.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] Deeds' Dayton Engineering Laboratories Company (DELCO automotive ignition, starters and generators), and the Perlman Rim Corporation.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] Sloan, who had been president of Hyatt, as president of United Motors.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] In the next two years, Sloan bought the Harrison Radiator Corporation, Lovell-McConnell Manufacturing Company (renamed Klaxon company to make Klaxon horns) in September 1916, and organized United Motors Service to sell and service the entire line of products nationwide.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] United Motors was originally independent of General Motors, selling to all manufacturers until 1918, when the company was acquired by General Motors for $45 million (three quarters debentures and one quarter common shares) and integrated into GM on December 31, 1918.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] United Motors became United Motors Service and continued to operate essentially as it had before.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] However, all of its production was now devoted to GM's brands.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] Sloan continued as the division manager, which carried with it a GM vice-president title and a position on the GM board.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] In 1923 he became President of General Motors and was Chairman when he retired in 1956.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] Charles Kettering, co-founder of Delco, was head of research at General Motors for 27 years.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] Harrison was President of Harrison Radiator until his death in 1927.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] Durant lost control of GM for the final time in 1920.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] United Motors Service would become a fully integrated division of General Motors in 1944.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] Around 1960, the division's name was changed to United Delco.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] With the Delco name becoming more well known with consumers, the “Delco” name was incorporated into all of the division's branches (Delco Remy, Delco Harrison, Delco Packard (Packard Electric), Delco Moraine).
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] A red and blue semicircular logo was implemented, designed by Lance Wyman (who would later famously design the graphic identity for the 1968 Mexico City Olympics, among other projects).
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] In 1899, Albert Champion came to the U.S. as a champion bicycle racer.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] He founded the Champion Spark Plug Company with the Stranahan brothers in 1905 and began production in 1907.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] Durant of the Buick Motor Co. asked to see some of Champion's prototypes.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] Buick at that time was using Rajah spark plugs.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] Durant thought they could manufacture spark plugs to Champion's design cheaper than buying them from Rajah, and set Champion up in a workshop in Flint, Michigan as part of the budding auto industry there.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] Champion went to work producing spark plugs to be used in Buick automobiles.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] Champion and Durant formed "Champion Ignition Co." Very shortly later, the Stranahan brothers ("Champion Spark Plug Co.") informed them they could not use the name "Champion" as they had it trademarked, so Champion changed the name to Champion's initials, AC Spark Plug.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] In 1927 AC Spark Plugs was bought by General Motors.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] In 1974, in an effort to streamline its operations and marketing, General Motors merged AC Spark Plug's aftersales operation with United Delco to create the new AC-Delco (Albert Champion Dayton Engineering Laboratories Company.) AC-Delco then marketed various AC and Delco-branded products.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] The hyphen was dropped and ACDelco received a new logo and marketing initiative.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/acdelco] The "AC" bullseye and semicircular Delco logo disappeared from product packaging.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Albania was inhabited by several Illyrian tribes, among them the Ardiaei, Bylliones, Dassaretii, Enchele, and Taulantians, with the Chaonians settled in the southwest.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Several colonies were founded by the Ancient Greeks along the Albanian coast, most notably Apollonia.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The Illyrians were the dominant power in Albania before the rise of Macedon.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Following the Illyrian Wars, Albania was integrated into the Roman Empire and remained in the Byzantine Empire after its partition.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] During the Middle Ages, several Albanian principalities emerged, most notably the Principality of Arbanon, Kingdom of Albania, Principality of Albania and Albania Veneta.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] In the 15th century, Albania became a center of resistance against Ottoman expansion under the leadership of Gjergj Kastrioti Skanderbeg, whose military campaigns repelled Ottoman advances for over two decades.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Although incorporated into the Ottoman Empire, Albania retained distinct cultural and social identities throughout four centuries of foreign rule, culminating in the Albanian Renaissance in the 19th century.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Albania declared independence in 1912, followed by a turbulent 20th century marked by monarchy, foreign occupation during both World Wars, and a communist regime under Enver Hoxha.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Since its independence in 1912, Albania has undergone a number of political changes, transitioning from a monarchy to a communist regime before becoming a sovereign parliamentary constitutional republic.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Governed by a constitution prioritising the separation of powers, the country's political structure includes a parliament, a ceremonial president, a functional prime minister and a hierarchy of courts.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Albania is a developing country with an upper-middle income economy driven by the service sector, with manufacturing and tourism, which attracted over 11 million visitors in 2024, also playing significant roles.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The illegal drug trade in Albania contributes around US$100 million to the economy per year.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] After the dissolution of its communist system, the country shifted from centralised planning to an open market economy.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Albanian citizens have universal health care access and free primary and secondary education.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The country is an official candidate for membership in the European Union, and has been negotiating accession since 2022.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The origin of the name "Albania" can be traced back to medieval Latin and the association with the Illyrian tribe of the Albani.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] This connection is further supported by the writings of the Ancient Greek geographer Ptolemy during the 2nd century AD, where he included the settlement of Albanopolis situated to the northeast of Durrës.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The presence of a medieval settlement named Albanon or Arbanon hints at the possibility of historical continuity.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The precise relationship between these historical references and the question of whether Albanopolis was synonymous with Albanon remain subjects of scholarly debate.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The Byzantine historian Michael Attaliates, in his 11th-century historical account, provides the earliest undisputed reference to the Albanians, when he mentions them as participants in a revolt against Constantinople in 1079.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] He also identifies the Arbanitai as subjects of the Duke of Dyrrachium.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] In the Middle Ages, Albania was denoted as *Arbëri* or *Arbëni* by its inhabitants, who identified themselves as *Arbëreshë* or *Arbëneshë*.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Albanians employ the terms *Shqipëri* or *Shqipëria* for their nation, designations that trace their historical origins to the 14th century.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] But only in the late 17th and early 18th centuries did these terms gradually supersede *Arbëria* and *Arbëreshë* among Albanians.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] These two expressions are widely interpreted to symbolise "Children of the Eagles" and "Land of the Eagles".
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Mesolithic habitation in Albania has been evidenced in several open-air sites which were close to the Adriatic coastline and in caves.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Mesolithic objects found in a cave near Xarrë include flint and jasper objects along with fossilised animal bones, while those discoveries at Mount Dajt comprise bone and stone tools similar to those of the Aurignacian culture.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The Neolithic era in Albania began around 7000 BC and is evidenced in finds which indicate domestication of sheep and goats and small-scale agriculture.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] A part of the Neolithic population may have been the same as the Mesolithic population of the southern Balkans, like in the Konispol cave, where the Mesolithic stratum co-exists with Pre-Pottery Neolithic finds.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Cardium pottery culture appears in coastal Albania and across the Adriatic after 6500 BC, while the settlements of the interior took part in the processes that formed the Starčevo culture.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The Albanian bitumen mines of Selenicë provide early evidence of bitumen exploitation in Europe, dating to Late Neolithic Albania (from 5000 BC), when local communities used it as pigment for ceramic decoration, waterproofing, and adhesive for repairing broken vessels.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The bitumen of Selenicë circulated towards eastern Albania from the early 5th millennium BC.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] First evidence of its overseas trade export comes from the Neolithic and Bronze Age southern Italy.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The high-quality bitumen of Selenicë has been exploited throughout all the historical ages since the Late Neolithic era until today.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The Indo-Europeanisation of Albania in the context of the IE-isation of the western Balkans began after 2800 BC.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The presence of the Early Bronze Age tumuli in the vicinity of later Apollonia dates to 2679±174 calBC (2852–2505 calBC).
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] These burial mounds belong to the southern expression of the Adriatic-Ljubljana culture (related to the later Cetina culture), which moved southwards along the Adriatic from the northern Balkans.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The same community built similar mounds in Montenegro (Rakića Kuće) and northern Albania (Shtoj).
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The first archaeogenetic find related to the IE-isation of Albania involves a man with predominantly Yamnaya ancestry buried in a tumulus of northeastern Albania, which dates to 2663–2472 calBC.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] During the Middle Bronze Age, Cetina culture sites and finds appear in Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Cetina culture moved southwards across the Adriatic from the Cetina valley of Dalmatia.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The incorporated territory of Albania was historically inhabited by Indo-European peoples, amongst them numerous Illyrian and Epirote tribes.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The territory referred to as Illyria corresponded roughly to the area east of the Adriatic Sea in the Mediterranean Sea, extending in the south to the mouth of the Vjosë.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The first account of the Illyrian groups comes from the Periplus of the Euxine Sea, a Greek text written in the 4th century BC.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The Bryges were also present in central Albania, while the south was inhabited by the Epirote Chaonians, whose capital was at Phoenice.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Other colonies, such as Apollonia and Epidamnos, were established by Greek city-states on the coast by the 7th century BC.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The Illyrian Taulanti were a powerful Illyrian tribe among the earliest recorded tribes in the area.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] They lived in an area that corresponds with much of present-day Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Together with the Dardanian ruler Cleitus, Glaucias, the ruler of the Taulantian kingdom, fought against Alexander the Great at the Battle of Pelium in 335 BC.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] As time passed, the ruler of Ancient Macedonia, Cassander of Macedon, captured Apollonia and crossed the river Genusus (Albanian: *Shkumbin*) in 314 BC.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] A few years later, Glaucias laid siege to Apollonia and captured the Greek colony of Epidamnos.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The Illyrian Ardiaei tribe, centred in Montenegro, ruled over most of the territory of northern Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Their Ardiaean Kingdom reached its greatest extent under King Agron, the son of Pleuratus II.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Agron extended his rule over other neighbouring tribes as well.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Following Agron's death in 230 BC, his wife, Teuta, inherited the Ardiaean kingdom.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Teuta's forces extended their operations further southwards to the Ionian Sea.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] In 229 BC, Rome declared war on the kingdom for extensively plundering Roman ships.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The war ended in an Illyrian defeat in 227 BC.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Teuta was eventually succeeded by Gentius in 181 BC.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Gentius clashed with the Romans in 168 BC, initiating the Third Illyrian War.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The conflict resulted in the Roman conquest of the region by 167 BC.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The Romans split the region into three administrative divisions.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The Roman Empire was split in 395 upon the death of Theodosius I into an Eastern and Western Roman Empire, in part because of the increasing pressure from threats during the Barbarian Invasions.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] From the 6th century into the 7th century, the Slavs crossed the Danube and largely absorbed the indigenous Greeks, Illyrians, and Thracians in the Balkans; thus, the Illyrians were mentioned for the last time in historical records in the 7th century.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] In the 11th century, the Great Schism formalised the break of communion between the Eastern Orthodox and Western Catholic Church, which is reflected in Albania through the emergence of a Catholic north and Orthodox south.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The Albanian people inhabited the west of Lake Ochrida and the upper valley of the River Shkumbin and established the Principality of Arbanon in 1190 under the leadership of Progon of Kruja.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The realm was succeeded by his sons Gjin Progoni and Demetrio Progoni.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Upon the death of Dhimiter, the territory came under the rule of the Albanian-Greek Gregorios Kamonas and subsequently under the Golem of Kruja.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] In the 13th century, the principality was dissolved.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Arbanon is considered to be the first sketch of an Albanian state, which retained a semi-autonomous status as the western extremity of the Byzantine Empire, under the Byzantine Doukai of Epirus or Laskarids of Nicaea.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Towards the end of the 12th and beginning of the 13th centuries, Serbs and Venetians began to take possession of the territory.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The ethnogenesis of the Albanians is uncertain; however, the first undisputed mention of Albanians dates back in historical records from 1079 or 1080 in a work by Michael Attaleiates, who referred to the Albanoi as having taken part in a revolt against Constantinople.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] At this point, the Albanians were fully Christianised.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] After the dissolution of Arbanon, Charles I of Anjou concluded an agreement with the Albanian rulers, promising to protect them and their ancient liberties.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] In 1272, he established the Kingdom of Albania and conquered regions back from the Despotate of Epirus.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The kingdom claimed all of central Albania territory from Dyrrhachium along the Adriatic Sea coast down to Butrint.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] A Catholic political structure was a basis for the papal plans of spreading Catholicism in the Balkan Peninsula.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] This plan also found the support of Helen of Anjou.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Around 30 Catholic churches and monasteries were built during her rule, mainly in northern Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Internal power struggles within the Byzantine Empire in the 14th century enabled Serbs' most powerful medieval ruler, Stefan Dušan, to establish a short-lived empire that included all of Albania except Durrës.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] In 1367, Albanian rulers established the Despotate of Arta.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] During that time, several Albanian principalities were established, notably the Principality of Albania, the Principality of Kastrioti, the Lordship of Berat, and the Principality of Dukagjini.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] In the first half of the 15th century, the Ottoman Empire invaded most of Albania, and the League of Lezhë was organized under Skanderbeg as a ruler, who became the national hero of the Albanian medieval history.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] that halted Ottoman advance into Europe for 25 years.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] With the fall of Constantinople, the Ottoman Empire entered an extended period of military conquest and expansion, with its borders gradually expanding deep into Southeast Europe.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] In 1385, they reached the Albanian Ionian Sea Coast, while in 1415, they established their garrisons across Southern Albania, eventually occupying most of Albania in 1431.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Thousands of Albanians consequently fled to Western Europe, particularly to Calabria, Naples, Ragusa, and Sicily, while numerous others sought protection at the often inaccessible Mountains of Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Since the vast majority of Albanians were adherents of Christianity, they were considered an inferior class of people, resulting in them being discriminated against in various forms, including being subjected to heavy taxes.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Additionally, the Devshirme system allowed the Sultan to collect a requisite percentage of Christian adolescents from their families to compose the Janissary.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The Ottoman conquest was also accompanied by the gradual process of Islamisation and the rapid construction of mosques.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] A prosperous and longstanding revolution erupted after the formation of the League of Lezhë until the fall of Shkodër under the leadership of Gjergj Kastrioti Skanderbeg, who consistently defeated major Ottoman armies led by Sultans Murad II and Mehmed II.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Skanderbeg managed to unite several of the Albanian principalities, amongst them the Arianitis, Dukagjinis, Zaharias, and Thopias, and establish a centralised authority over most of the non-conquered territories, becoming the Lord of Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Despite his competence as a military leader, Skanderbeg's victories over the Ottoman Empire's military had only a short-term impact, as his forces were unable to halt the Ottomans' advancement permanently; therefore, they successfully delayed the final conquest of Albanian lands only temporarily.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The constant Ottoman invasions caused enormous destruction to Albania, greatly reducing the population and destroying flocks of livestock and crops.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Besides surrender, there was no possible way Skanderbeg would be able to halt the Ottoman invasions despite his military forces achieving several consecutive victories against them.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Among other factors, his manpower and resources were insufficient for a prolonged war, preventing him from expanding the war efforts and driving the Turks from the Albanian borders.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Albania was therefore doomed to face an unending series of Ottoman attacks until it eventually fell years after his death.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] When the Ottomans were gaining a firm foothold in the region, Albanian towns were organised into four principal sanjaks.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The government fostered trade by settling a sizeable Jewish colony of refugees fleeing persecution in Spain.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The city of Vlorë saw passing through its ports imported merchandise from Europe, such as velvets, cotton goods, mohairs, carpets, spices, and leather from Bursa and Constantinople.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Some citizens of Vlorë even had business associates throughout Europe.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The phenomenon of Islamisation among the Albanians became primarily widespread from the 17th century and continued into the 18th century.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Islam offered them equal opportunities and advancement within the Ottoman Empire.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] However, according to some scholars, motives for conversion were diverse depending on the context; although the lack of source material significantly hampers efforts to investigate such issues.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] As a result of the Ottomans' increasing suppression of Catholicism, most Catholic Albanians converted in the 17th century, while Orthodox Albanians followed suit mainly in the following century.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Since the Albanian-inhabited regions were considered strategically important, Albanians made up a significant proportion of the Ottoman Empire's military and bureaucracy.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Consequently, many Muslim Albanians attained important political and military positions, while their work made a significant cultural contribution to the broader Muslim world.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Enjoying this privileged position, they held various high administrative positions, which, among others, included over two dozen Albanians serving as Grand viziers of the Ottoman Empire.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Additionally, other distinguished Albanians included members of the prominent Köprülü family, Zagan Pasha, Muhammad Ali of Egypt, and Ali Pasha of Tepelena.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Furthermore, two Ottoman sultans, Bayezid II and Mehmed III, were born to mothers of Albanian ethnic backgrounds.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The Albanian Renaissance was a period with its roots in the late 18th century and continuing into the 19th century, during which the Albanian people gathered spiritual and intellectual strength for an independent cultural and political life within an independent nation.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Modern Albanian culture flourished too, especially Albanian literature and arts, and was frequently linked to the influences of the Romanticism and Enlightenment principles.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Prior to the rise of nationalism, Ottoman authorities suppressed any expression of national unity or conscience by the Albanian people.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The victory of Russia over the Ottoman Empire following the Russian-Ottoman Wars resulted the execution of the Treaty of San Stefano which assigned Albanian-populated lands to their Slavic and Greek neighbours.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] However, the United Kingdom and Austro-Hungarian Empire consequently blocked the arrangement and caused the Treaty of Berlin.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] From this point, Albanians started to organise themselves with the goal to protect and unite the Albanian-populated lands into a unitary nation, leading to the formation of the League of Prizren.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The league had initially the assistance of the Ottoman authorities whose position was based on the religious solidarity of Muslim people and landlords connected with the Ottoman administration.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] They favoured and protected the Muslim solidarity and called for defence of Muslim lands simultaneously constituting the reason for titling the league Committee of the Real Muslims.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Approximately 300 Muslims participated in the assembly composed by delegates from Bosnia, the administrator of the Sanjak of Prizren as representatives of the central authorities and no delegates from Vilayet of Scutari.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Ottomans authorities cancelled their assistance when the league, under Abdyl Frashëri, became focused on working towards Albanian autonomy and requested merging four vilayets, including Kosovo, Shkodër, Monastir and Ioannina, into a unified vilayet, the Albanian Vilayet.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The league used military force to prevent the annexing areas of Plav and Gusinje assigned to Montenegro.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] After several successful battles with Montenegrin troops, such as the Battle of Novšiće, the league was forced to retreat from their contested regions.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The league was later defeated by the Ottoman army sent by the sultan.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Albania declared independence from the Ottoman Empire on 28 November 1912, accompanied by the establishment of the Senate and Government by the Assembly of Vlorë on 4 December 1912.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Its sovereignty was recognised by the Conference of London.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] On 29 July 1913, the Treaty of London delineated the borders of the country and its neighbors, leaving many Albanians outside Albania, predominantly partitioned between Montenegro, Serbia, and Greece.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Headquartered in Vlorë, the International Commission of Control was established on 15 October 1913 to take care of the administration of Albania until its own political institutions were in order.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The International Gendarmerie was established as the Principality of Albania's first law enforcement agency.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] In November, the first gendarmerie members arrived in the country.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Prince of Albania Wilhelm of Wied *(Princ Vilhelm Vidi)* was selected as the first prince of the principality.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] On 7 March, he arrived in the provisional capital of Durrës and began to organise his government, appointing Turhan Pasha Përmeti to form the first Albanian cabinet.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] In November 1913, the Albanian pro-Ottoman forces had offered the throne of Albania to the Ottoman war minister of Albanian origin, Ahmed Izzet Pasha.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The pro-Ottoman peasants believed that the new regime was a tool of the six Christian Great Powers and local landowners, who owned half of the arable land.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] In February 1914, the Autonomous Republic of Northern Epirus was proclaimed in Gjirokastër by the local Greek population against incorporation to Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] This initiative was short-lived, and in 1921 the southern provinces were incorporated into the Albanian Principality.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] High-ranking Orthodox clergy were among the strongest opponents of the Albanian National Awakening.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Reports from the period, including those from international observers, documented the burning of villages and civilian casualties.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Nationalist Orthodox insurgents were accused of targeting Muslim Albanian populations to consolidate territorial claims for Greece.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Meanwhile, the revolt of Albanian peasants against the new regime erupted under the leadership of the group of Muslim clerics gathered around Essad Pasha Toptani, who proclaimed himself the savior of Albania and Islam.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] To gain the support of the Mirdita Catholic volunteers from northern Albania, Prince Wied appointed their leader, Prênk Bibë Doda, foreign minister of the Principality of Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] In May and June 1914, the International Gendarmerie was joined by Isa Boletini and his men, mostly from Kosovo, and the rebels defeated northern Mirdita Catholics, capturing most of Central Albania by the end of August 1914.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Prince Wied's regime collapsed, and he left the country on 3 September 1914.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The interwar period in Albania was marked by persistent economic and social difficulties, political instability and foreign interventions.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] After World War I, Albania lacked an established government and internationally recognised borders, rendering it vulnerable to neighboring entities such as Greece, Italy, and Yugoslavia, all of which sought to expand their influence.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] This led to political uncertainty, highlighted in 1918 when the Congress of Durrës sought Paris Peace Conference protection but was denied, further complicating Albania's position on the international stage.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Territorial tensions escalated as Yugoslavia, particularly Serbia, sought control of northern Albania, while Greece aimed dominance in southern Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The situation deteriorated in 1919 when the Serbs launched attacks on Albanian inhabitants, among others in Gusinje and Plav, resulting in massacres and large-scale displacement.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Meanwhile, Italian influence continued to expand during this time, driven by economic interests and political ambitions.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Fan Noli, renowned for his idealism, became prime minister in 1924, with a vision to institute a Western-style constitutional government, abolish feudalism, counter Italian influence, and enhance critical sectors, including infrastructure, education and healthcare.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] He faced resistance from former allies, who had assisted in the removal of Zog from power, and struggled to secure foreign aid to implement his agenda.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Noli's decision to establish diplomatic ties with the Soviet Union, an adversary of the Serbian elite, ignited allegations of bolshevism from Belgrade.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] This in turn led to increased pressure from Italy and culminated in Zog's restoration to authority.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] In 1928, Zog transitioned Albania from a republic to a monarchy that garnered backing from Fascist Italy, with Zog assuming the title of King Zog I.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Key constitutional changes dissolved the Senate and established a unicameral National Assembly while preserving Zog's authoritative powers.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] In 1939, Italy under Benito Mussolini launched a military invasion of Albania, resulting in the exile of Zog and the creation of an Italian protectorate.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] As World War II progressed, Italy aimed to expand its territorial dominion in the Balkans, including territorial claims on regions of Greece (Chameria), Macedonia, Montenegro and Kosovo.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] These ambitions laid the foundation of Greater Albania, which aimed to unite all areas with Albanian-majority populations into a single country.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] In 1943, as Italy's control declined, Nazi Germany assumed control of Albania, subjecting Albanians to forced labour, economic exploitation and repression under German rule.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] This period saw the forced expulsion and massacres of the Cham Albanians, a predominantly Muslim group.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The religious divide was used as a justification for violence, with some Orthodox locals reportedly identifying Muslim neighbors to paramilitary groups, leading to massacres and the forced expulsion of thousands.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The tide shifted in 1944 when Albanian partisan forces, under the leadership of Enver Hoxha and other communist leaders, successfully liberated Albania from German occupation.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The establishment of the People's Republic of Albania under the leadership of Enver Hoxha was a significant epoch in modern Albanian history.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Hoxha's regime embraced Marxist–Leninist ideologies and implemented authoritarian policies, including prohibition of religious practices, severe restrictions on travel, and abolition of private property rights.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] It was also defined by a persistent pattern of purges, extensive repression, instances of betrayal, and hostility to external influences.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Any form of opposition or resistance to his rule was met with expeditious and severe consequences, such as internal exile, extended imprisonment, and execution.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The regime confronted a multitude of challenges, including widespread poverty, illiteracy, health crises and gender inequality.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] In response, Hoxha initiated a modernisation initiative aimed at attaining economic and social liberation and transforming Albania into an industrial society.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Albania's diplomatic history under Hoxha was characterised by notable conflicts.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Initially aligned with Yugoslavia as a satellite state, the relationship deteriorated as Yugoslavia aimed to incorporate Albania within its territory.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Subsequently, Albania established relations with the Soviet Union and engaged trade agreements with other Eastern European countries, but experienced disagreements over Soviet policies, leading to strained ties with Moscow and diplomatic separation in 1961.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Simultaneously, tensions with the West heightened due to Albania's refusal to hold free elections and allegations of Western support for anti-communist uprisings.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Albania's enduring partnership was with China; it sided with Beijing during the Sino-Soviet conflict, resulting in severed ties with the Soviet Union and withdrawal from the Warsaw Pact in response to the invasion of Czechoslovakia in 1968.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] But their relations stagnated in 1970, prompting both to reassess their commitment, and Albania actively reduced its dependence on China.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Under Hoxha's regime, Albania underwent a widespread campaign targeting religious clergy of various faiths, resulting in public persecution and executions, particularly targeting Muslims, Roman Catholics and Eastern Orthodox adherents.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] In 1946, religious estates underwent nationalisation, coinciding with the closure or transformation of religious institutions into various other purposes.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] This culminated in 1976, when Albania became the world's first constitutionally atheist state.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Under this regime, citizens were forced to renounce their religious beliefs, adopt a secular way of life, and embrace socialist ideology.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] After four decades of communism paired with the revolutions of 1989, Albania witnessed a notable rise in political activism, particularly among students, which led to a transformation in the prevailing order.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] After the first multi-party elections of 1991, the communist party maintained a stronghold in the parliament until its defeat in the parliamentary elections of 1992 directed by the Democratic Party.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Considerable economic and financial resources were devoted to pyramid schemes that were widely supported by the government.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The schemes swept up somewhere between one sixth and one third of the population of the country.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Despite the International Monetary Fund's warnings, Sali Berisha defended the schemes as large investment firms, leading more people to redirect their remittances and sell their homes and cattle for cash to deposit in the schemes.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The schemes began to collapse in late 1996, leading many of the investors to join initially peaceful protests against the government, requesting their money back.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The protests turned violent in February 1997 as government forces responded by firing on the demonstrators.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] In March, the Police and Republican Guard deserted, leaving their armories open.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] These were promptly emptied by militias and criminal gangs.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The resulting civil war caused a wave of evacuations of foreign nationals and refugees.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The crisis led both Aleksandër Meksi and Sali Berisha to resign from office in the wake of the general election.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] In April 1997, Operation Alba, a U.N. peacekeeping force led by Italy, entered Albania with two goals: to assist with the evacuation of expatriates and secure the ground for international organisations.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The main international organisation involved was the Western European Union's multinational Albanian Police element, which worked with the government to restructure the judicial system and simultaneously the Albanian police.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] After the fall of the communist system, Albania pursued integration with Euro-Atlantic institutions.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] It formally applied for membership of the European Union on 28 April 2009 and joined NATO the same year.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Albania was granted EU candidate status in June 2014, while accession negotiations began with the first intergovernmental conference in July 2022.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Albania opened negotiations on the fundamentals cluster in October 2024 and, by late 2025, had opened all negotiating clusters, a development described by the European Commission as a significant milestone in the accession process.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The 2013 Albanian parliamentary election ended eight years of Democratic Party rule under Sali Berisha.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The Socialist Party, led by Edi Rama, won the election as the main force of the Alliance for a European Albania, with the Socialist Movement for Integration as a coalition partner.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Rama's governments promoted judicial reform, public administration changes, urban redevelopment, digitalisation of public services, tourism development and EU accession as central priorities.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] A major justice reform package adopted in 2016 created new institutions including the Special Structure against Corruption and Organized Crime (SPAK), which later became central to the prosecution of high-level corruption and organised crime cases.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] At the same time, Rama's long tenure became increasingly controversial.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The Socialist Party won the 2017, 2021 and 2025 parliamentary elections, making Rama the first Albanian prime minister to secure four consecutive mandates.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] His dominance was accompanied by persistent criticism from opposition parties, civil society and international monitors over corruption, weak checks and balances, state capture, media pressure and the use of state resources in elections.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Freedom House has classified Albania as "Partly Free" and as a "Transitional or Hybrid Regime", while noting that elections are competitive but that politics is highly polarised, organised around dominant personalities, and affected by corruption and bribery.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Freedom House's *Nations in Transit* assessment described Albania's national governance as democratic but dominated by clientelist party politics and individual personalities, and stated that elections were frequently marred by vote-buying, manipulation, fraud and gerrymandering.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Concerns about state capture also became a recurring theme in assessments of Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] In 2021, Transparency International and the Institute for Democracy and Mediation published *Deconstructing State Capture in Albania*, a report examining grand corruption cases and "tailor-made laws" from 2008 to 2020.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The report argued that state-capture mechanisms in Albania involved clientelist networks, corruption in the judiciary and laws designed to benefit particular private interests.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Electoral integrity remained disputed during Rama's later terms.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The OSCE Office for Democratic Institutions and Human Rights stated that the 2025 Albanian parliamentary election was competitive and professionally managed, but that it took place in a highly polarised environment and contestants did not enjoy a level playing field.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The final report cited reports of intimidation, misuse of public resources and pressure on public employees, which undermined equal opportunities.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Reuters reported that the 2025 campaign was dominated by Rama's promise to secure EU membership by 2030 and by accusations of widespread corruption, while critics argued that he had concentrated too much power.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] After the election, Rama began his fourth term in September 2025 and declared EU membership by 2030 the central goal of his mandate.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The consolidation of Rama's rule coincided with a wave of investigations by SPAK against high-ranking figures from both the governing majority and the opposition.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Deputy prime minister and infrastructure minister Belinda Balluku was later investigated over public-tender allegations, denied wrongdoing, and was dismissed by Rama in February 2026 as the case intensified.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] European Union officials praised SPAK's work as central to rule-of-law reform, while also warning that Albania's EU progress depended on judicial independence and credible anti-corruption results.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] On 26 November 2019, a 6.4 magnitude earthquake struck Albania, with the epicentre about 16 km (10 mi) southwest of Mamurras.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The tremor was felt in Tirana and in places as far away as Taranto, Italy, and Belgrade, Serbia, while the most affected areas were Durrës and Kodër-Thumanë.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The response included humanitarian aid from the Albanian diaspora and several foreign governments.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] On 9 March 2020, the COVID-19 pandemic was confirmed to have spread to Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] In 2026, large anti-government demonstrations known as the Flamingo Revolution emerged after proposed luxury coastal developments on Sazan Island and the Zvërnec peninsula, including projects linked to Jared Kushner, became a focus of environmental and anti-corruption protests.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] Demonstrators accused Rama's government of lacking transparency, endangering protected ecosystems and failing to tackle corruption or improve public services.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] The protests, initially centred on environmental protection, expanded into broader demands for government accountability, early elections and Rama's resignation.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p01] European Parliament figures also warned that the coastal-development plans could affect Albania's EU accession process if they conflicted with environmental obligations and democratic standards.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Albania lies along the Mediterranean Sea on the Balkan Peninsula in South and Southeast Europe, and has an area of 28,748 km2 (11,100 sq mi).
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] It is bordered by the Adriatic Sea to the west, Montenegro to the northwest, Kosovo to the northeast, North Macedonia to the east, Greece to the south, and the Ionian Sea to the southwest.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] It is between latitudes 42° and 39° N and longitudes 21° and 19° E.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Geographic coordinates include Vërmosh at 42° 35' 34" northern latitude as the northernmost point, Konispol at 39° 40' 0" northern latitude as the southernmost, Sazan at 19° 16' 50" eastern longitude as the westernmost, and Vërnik at 21° 1' 26" eastern longitude as the easternmost.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Mount Korab, rising at 2,764 m (9,068.24 ft) above the Adriatic, is the highest point, while the Mediterranean Sea, at 0 m (0.00 ft), is the lowest.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The country extends 148 km (92 mi) from east to west and around 340 km (211 mi) from north to south.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Albania has a diverse and varied landscape with mountains and hills that traverse its territory in various directions.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The country is home to extensive mountain ranges, including the Albanian Alps in the north, the Korab Mountains in the east, the Pindus Mountains in the southeast, the Ceraunian Mountains in the southwest, and the Skanderbeg Mountains in the centre.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] In the northwest is the Lake of Shkodër, Southern Europe's largest lake.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Towards the southeast emerges the Lake of Ohrid, one of the world's oldest continuously existing lakes.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Farther south, the expanse includes the Large and Small Lake of Prespa, some of the Balkans' highest lakes.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Rivers rise mostly in the east and discharge into the Adriatic and Ionian Seas.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The country's longest river, measured from mouth to source, is the Drin, which starts at the confluence of its two headwaters, the Black and White Drin.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Of particular concern is the Vjosë, one of Europe's last intact large river systems.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] In Albania forest cover is around 29.% of the total land area, equivalent to 788,900 hectares (ha) of forest in 2020, up from 788,800 hectares (ha) in 1990.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Of the naturally regenerating forest 11% was reported to be primary forest (consisting of native tree species with no clearly visible indications of human activity) and around 0% of the forest area was found within protected areas.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] For the year 2015, 97% of the forest area was reported to be under public ownership, 3% private ownership and 0% with ownership listed as other or unknown.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The climate of Albania exhibits a distinguished level of variability and diversity due to the differences in latitude, longitude and altitude.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Albania experiences a Mediterranean and Continental climate, characterised by the presence of four distinct seasons.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] According to the Köppen classification, Albania encompasses five primary climatic types, spanning from Mediterranean and subtropical in the western half to oceanic, continental and subarctic in the eastern half of the country.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The coastal regions along the Adriatic and Ionian Seas in Albania are acknowledged as the warmest areas, while the northern and eastern regions encompassing the Albanian Alps and the Korab Mountains are recognised as the coldest areas in the country.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Throughout the year, the average monthly temperatures fluctuate, ranging from −1 °C (30 °F) during the winter months to 21.8 °C (71.2 °F) in the summer months.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Notably, the highest recorded temperature of 43.9 °C (111.0 °F) was observed in Kuçovë on 18 July 1973, while the lowest temperature of −29 °C (−20 °F) was recorded in Shtyllë, Librazhd on 9 January 2017.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Albania receives most of the precipitation in winter months and less in summer months.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The average precipitation is about 1,485 millimetres (58.5 inches).
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The mean annual precipitation ranges between 600 and 3,000 millimetres (24 and 118 inches) depending on geographical location.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The northwestern and southeastern highlands receive the intenser amount of precipitation, whilst the northeastern and southwestern highlands as well as the Western Lowlands the more limited amount.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The Albanian Alps in the far north of the country are considered to be among the most humid regions of Europe, receiving at least 3,100 mm (122.0 in) of rain annually.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Four glaciers within these mountains were discovered at a relatively low altitude of 2,000 metres (6,600 ft), which is extremely rare for such a southerly latitude.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] A biodiversity hotspot, Albania possesses an exceptionally rich and contrasting biodiversity on account of its geographical location at the centre of the Mediterranean Sea and the great diversity in its climatic, geological and hydrological conditions.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The estuaries, wetlands and lakes are extraordinarily important for the greater flamingo, pygmy cormorant and the extremely rare and perhaps the most iconic bird of the country, the dalmatian pelican.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Of particular importance are the Mediterranean monk seal, loggerhead sea turtle and green sea turtle that use to nest on the country's coastal waters and shores.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] In terms of phytogeography, Albania is part of the Boreal Kingdom and stretches specifically within the Illyrian province of the Circumboreal and Mediterranean Region.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Its territory can be subdivided into four terrestrial ecoregions of the Palearctic realm namely within the Illyrian deciduous forests, Balkan mixed forests, Pindus Mountains mixed forests and Dinaric Mountains mixed forests.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Approximately 3,500 different species of plants can be found in Albania which refers principally to a Mediterranean and Eurasian character.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The country maintains a vibrant tradition of herbal and medicinal practices.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] At the minimum 300 plants growing locally are used in the preparation of herbs and medicines.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The trees within the forests are primarily fir, oak, beech and pine.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Albania has been an active participant in numerous international agreements and conventions aimed at strengthing its commitment to the preservation and sustainable management of biological diversity.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Since 1994, the country is a party to the Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD) and its associated Cartagena and Nagoya Protocols.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] To uphold these commitments, it has developed and implemented a comprehensive National Biodiversity Strategy and Action Plan (NBSAP).
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Furthermore, Albania has established a partnership with the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN), advancing its conservation efforts on both national and international scales.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Guided by the IUCN, the country has made substantial progress in the foundation of protected areas within its boundaries, encompassing 12 national parks among others Butrint, Karaburun-Sazan, Llogara, Prespa and Vjosa.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] As a signatory to the Ramsar Convention, Albania has granted special recognition upon four wetlands, designating them as Wetlands of International Importance, including Buna-Shkodër, Butrint, Karavasta and Prespa.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The country's dedication to protection extends further into the sphere of UNESCO's World Network of Biosphere Reserves, operating within the framework of the Man and the Biosphere Programme, evidenced by its engagement in the Ohrid-Prespa Transboundary Biosphere Reserve.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Furthermore, Albania is host to two natural World Heritage Sites, which encompass the Ohrid region and both the Gashi River and Rrajca as part of Ancient and Primeval Beech Forests of the Carpathians and Other Regions of Europe.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The protected areas of Albania are areas designated and managed by the Albanian government.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] There are 12 national parks, 4 ramsar sites, 1 biosphere reserve and 786 other types of conservation reserves in Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Located in the north, the Albanian Alps National Park, comprising the former Theth National Park and Valbonë Valley National Park, is surrounded amidst the towering peaks of the Albanian Alps.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] In the east, portions of the rugged Korab, Nemërçka and Shebenik Mountains are conserved within the boundaries of Fir of Hotovë-Dangëlli National Park, Shebenik National Park and Prespa National Park, with the latter encompassing Albania's share of the Great and Small Lakes of Prespa.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] To the south, the Ceraunian Mountains define the Albanian Ionian Sea Coast, shaping the landscape of Llogara National Park, which extends into the Karaburun Peninsula, forming the Karaburun-Sazan Marine Park.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Further southward lies Butrint National Park, occupying a peninsula surrounded by the Lake of Butrint and the Channel of Vivari.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] In the west, stretching along the Albanian Adriatic Sea Coast, the Divjakë-Karavasta National Park boasts the extensive Lagoon of Karavasta, one of the largest lagoon systems in the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Notably, Europe's first wild river national park, Vjosa National Park, safeguards the Vjosa River and its primary tributaries, which originates in the Pindus Mountains and flows to the Adriatic Sea.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Dajti Mountain National Park, Lurë-Dejë Mountain National Park and Tomorr Mountain National Park protect the mountainous terrain of the centre of Albania, including the Tomorr and Skanderbeg Mountains.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Environmental issues in Albania notably encompass air and water pollution, climate change impacts, waste management shortcomings, biodiversity loss and imperative for nature conservation.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Climate change is predicted to exert significant impacts on the quality of life in Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Albania is one of the European countries most at risk and vulnerable to natural disasters.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Natural disasters, such as floods, forest fires, and landslides, are increasing in Albania due to climate change, causing significant damage.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Rising sea levels are anticipated to negatively impact coastal communities and the tourism industry.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] In 2023 Albania emitted 7.67 million tonnes of greenhouse gases, equivalent to 2.73 tonnes per person, making it a relatively low emitting country.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Albania has pledged a 20.9% reduction in GHG emissions by 2030, and net zero by 2050.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The country has a moderate and improving performance in the Environmental Performance Index with an overall ranking of 62 out of 180 countries in 2022.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] However, Albania's ranking has decreased since its highest placement at position 15 in the Environmental Performance Index of 2012.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Since declaring independence in 1912, Albania has undergone several major constitutional transformations, including a monarchy, a communist one-party state, and, following the collapse of communism, the establishment of a democratic parliamentary republic.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The current constitutional order was established with the adoption of the Constitution of Albania in 1998, creating a parliamentary constitutional republic based on the separation of powers between the legislature, executive and judiciary.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Executive authority is exercised by the Prime Minister and the Council of Ministers, while the President of Albania serves as head of state with largely ceremonial and constitutional responsibilities.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Legislative authority is vested in the unicameral Parliament of Albania, elected every four years through proportional representation.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Judicial authority is exercised by an independent judiciary headed by the Constitutional Court and the Supreme Court.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Since Edi Rama and the Socialist Party of Albania came to power in 2013, Albania has experienced an unprecedented concentration of executive power, with the Socialist Party winning four consecutive parliamentary elections in 2013, 2017, 2021 and 2025.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Supporters credit Rama's governments with accelerating European Union accession negotiations, implementing the 2016 justice reform, expanding digital public services, improving infrastructure and increasing tourism.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] At the same time, Rama's prolonged tenure has generated sustained domestic and international criticism.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Opposition parties, civil society organisations and a number of analysts have argued that Albania has experienced significant democratic backsliding characterised by increasing executive dominance, weakened institutional checks and balances, clientelist governance and extensive political patronage.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Freedom House describes Albania as a "Partly Free" country and notes that politics is dominated by powerful party leaders, while corruption remains a persistent challenge.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Its *Nations in Transit* report characterises Albania's national governance as being dominated by clientelist party politics and states that elections continue to be affected by vote-buying, manipulation, fraud and gerrymandering.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Concerns regarding state capture have also featured prominently in assessments of Albania's political system.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Electoral integrity has remained a contentious issue.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Following the 2025 Albanian parliamentary election, the OSCE Office for Democratic Institutions and Human Rights concluded that the election was competitive and professionally managed, but found that it was held in a highly polarised environment without a level playing field.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The observation mission reported misuse of public resources, pressure on public employees, intimidation allegations and unequal campaign conditions that undermined equal opportunities among contestants.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The European Commission has generally praised SPAK's work while continuing to stress that corruption remains prevalent in many sectors and that judicial independence must be protected from political pressure.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] During Rama's fourth term, anti-government demonstrations intensified.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Beginning in late 2025 and expanding further during the Flamingo Revolution in 2026, protesters accused the government of systemic corruption, lack of transparency, misuse of public resources and favouring politically connected business interests.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The protests, initially triggered by opposition to coastal development projects, evolved into broader demands for democratic reform, government accountability and Rama's resignation.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Human rights protections are guaranteed by the Constitution regardless of ethnicity, language, race or religion.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Nevertheless, international organisations continue to identify concerns regarding judicial independence, corruption, media pluralism and political influence over state institutions, while noting that progress in these areas remains closely linked to Albania's European Union accession process.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Emerging from decades of isolation following the fall of communism, Albania has adopted a foreign policy orientation centred on active cooperation and engagement in international affairs.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The external affairs of Albania underscore the country's dedication to regional stability and integration into major international institutions.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Albania became a member of the United Nations (UN) in 1955, shortly after emerging from a period of isolation during the communist era.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The country reached a major achievement in its foreign policy by securing NATO membership in 2009.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Since obtaining candidate status in 2014, the country has also embarked on a comprehensive reform agenda to align itself with European Union (EU) accession standards, with the objective of becoming an EU member state.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Albania and Kosovo maintain a fraternal relationship strengthened by their substantial cultural, ethnical and historical ties.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Both countries foster enduring diplomatic ties, with Albania actively supporting Kosovo's development and international integration efforts.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Its fundamental contribution to Kosovo's path to independence is underscored by its early recognition of Kosovo's sovereignty in 2008.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Furthermore, both governments hold annual joint meetings, displayed by the inaugural meeting in 2014, which serves as an official platform to enhance bilateral cooperation and reinforce their joint commitment to policies that promote the stability and prosperity of the broader Albanian region.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The Albanian Armed Forces consist of Land, Air and Naval Forces and constitute the military and paramilitary forces of the country.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] They are led by a commander-in-chief under the supervision of the Ministry of Defence and by the President as the supreme commander during wartime.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] However, in times of peace its powers are executed through the Prime Minister and the Defence Minister.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The chief purpose of the armed forces of Albania is the defence of the independence, the sovereignty and the territorial integrity of the country, as well as the participation in humanitarian, combat, non-combat and peace support operations.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Military service is voluntary since 2010 with the age of 19 being the legal minimum age for the duty.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Albania has committed to increase the participations in multinational operations.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Since the fall of communism, the country has participated in six international missions but only one United Nations mission in Georgia, where it sent three military observers.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Since February 2008, Albania has participated officially in NATO's Operation Active Endeavor in the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] It was invited to join NATO on 3 April 2008, and it became a full member on 2 April 2009.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Albania reduced the number of active troops from 65,000 in 1988 to 14,500 in 2009.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The military now consists mainly of a small fleet of aircraft and sea vessels.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Increasing the military budget was one of the most important conditions for NATO integration.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] As of 1996 military spending was an estimated 1.5% of the country's GDP, only to peak in 2009 at 2% and fall again to 1.5%.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Human rights in Albania are formally protected by the Constitution of Albania, which guarantees equality before the law, freedom of expression, freedom of assembly, religious freedom and protection from discrimination.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] International assessments generally describe Albania as a competitive but weakened democracy, with persistent problems involving corruption, political pressure on institutions, media freedom, gender-based violence, prison conditions and discrimination against vulnerable groups.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] During the long premiership of Edi Rama, whose Socialist Party of Albania has governed since 2013, human-rights concerns have often been linked to broader criticism of democratic backsliding, concentration of executive power, clientelist party politics and weak institutional checks.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Freedom House classifies Albania as "Partly Free" and states that corruption and bribery remain major problems, while its *Nations in Transit* assessment describes national governance as dominated by clientelist party politics and individual personalities.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Opposition parties and critics have characterised Rama's rule as increasingly authoritarian, while the government and its supporters point to judicial reform, European Union accession progress and the work of anti-corruption institutions as evidence of democratic consolidation.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Freedom of expression and media independence remain major concerns.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The United States Department of State's 2024 human-rights report identified serious restrictions on freedom of expression and media freedom, including journalist self-censorship, threats and smear campaigns against journalists reporting on alleged corruption.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Reporters Without Borders has stated that journalists in Albania face political pressure, especially during elections, as well as pressure from media owners and economic insecurity.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] In the 2026 World Press Freedom Index, Albania ranked 83rd of 180 countries, with media-rights groups noting continued structural problems affecting editorial independence and journalist safety.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Freedom of assembly is generally recognised, but protest policing has drawn attention during periods of political unrest.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Authorities said the police response followed attacks on officers and damage to property, while protesters and opposition figures accused the government of using force to suppress dissent.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Corruption also has direct implications for human rights and public trust in institutions.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] International reports have repeatedly identified corruption in government, law enforcement, the judiciary and local administration as a major problem.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] In 2021, Transparency International and the Institute for Democracy and Mediation argued that Albania showed signs of state capture through grand corruption, clientelist networks and tailor-made laws benefiting private interests.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Conditions in prisons and detention facilities have remained a human-rights concern.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Amnesty International reported that people in prisons experienced overcrowding and inadequate healthcare, while the Council of Europe and Albanian authorities have identified prison reform and protection of prisoners' rights as continuing priorities.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Civil-society submissions to the UN Committee against Torture have also raised concerns about overcrowding, poor detention conditions, limited access to legal representation and insufficient investigation of abuse allegations.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Violence against women and girls remains widespread.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Nearly 60% of women in rural areas suffer physical or psychological violence and nearly 8% are victims of sexual violence.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] In 2014 the Albanian Helsinki Committee (AHC) reported that the number of female murder victims remained high.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The Commissioner for Protection from Discrimination has raised concerns regarding the family registration law that discriminates against women.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] As a result, heads of households, who are overwhelmingly men, have the right to change family residency without their partners' permission.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] In 2024, the Council of Europe's GREVIO monitoring body reported progress in Albania's framework against violence against women, but said serious gaps remained, including persistent gender stereotypes, extremely low reporting of sexual violence and limited specialist services.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] In 2026, the United Nations in Albania welcomed the adoption of a new law on prevention and protection from violence against women and domestic violence.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Roma, Balkan Egyptian and other minority communities continue to face barriers in education, housing, employment and access to public services.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] In 2024, the UN Committee on the Elimination of Racial Discrimination reviewed Albania's implementation of anti-discrimination obligations and discussed the situation of Roma and Egyptian communities, including education, legal aid and hate-speech monitoring.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Albania has legal protections against discrimination based on sexual orientation and gender identity, and LGBT organisations hold public events such as Tirana Pride.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] In 2015, ILGA-Europe ranked Albania 19th in terms of LGBT rights out of 49 observed European countries.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] In the 2022 Rainbow Europe report, lack of progress caused Albania to be ranked 28th among 49 countries.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] ILGA-Europe's later country reporting continued to identify discrimination and unsafe school environments for LGBTI people, with a 2024–2025 nationwide survey by Aleanca LGBTI reporting that most respondents viewed schools as unsafe for marginalised groups, including LGBTI students.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] are the first-level administrative units in Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Albania is defined within a territorial area of 28,748 km2 (11,100 sq mi) in the Balkan Peninsula.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] It is informally divided into three regions, the Northern, Central and Southern Regions.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Since its Declaration of Independence in 1912, Albania has reformed its internal organisation 21 times.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Presently, the primary administrative units are the twelve constituent counties (*qarqe/qarqet*), which hold equal status under the law.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] Counties had previously been used in the 1950s and were recreated on 31 July 2000 to unify the 36 districts (*rrathë/rrathët*) of that time.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The largest county in Albania by population is Tirana County with over 800,000 people.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The smallest county, by population, is Gjirokastër County with over 70,000 people.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The largest county, by area, is Korçë County encompassing 3,711 square kilometres (1,433 sq mi) of the southeast of Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The smallest county, by area, is Durrës County with an area of 766 square kilometres (296 sq mi) in the west of Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The counties are made up of 61 second-level divisions known as municipalities (*bashki/bashkia*).
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] The municipalities are the first level of local governance, responsible for local needs and law enforcement.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] They unified and simplified the previous system of urban and rural municipalities or communes (*komuna/komunat*) in 2015.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] For smaller issues of local government, the municipalities are organised into 373 administrative units (*njësia*/*njësitë administrative*).
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p02] There are also 2980 villages (*fshatra/fshatrat*), neighborhoods or wards (*lagje/lagjet*), and localities (*lokalitete/lokalitetet*) previously used as administrative units.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Transitioning from a socialist planned to a capitalist mixed economy, Albania is classified as a developing open market with an upper-middle income status.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The Albanian economy is characterised by a substantial service sector, comprising 48.6% of GDP, with key contributions from wholesale and retail trade, tourism, real estate, and logistics.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Following this, the industrial sector accounts for 20.2%, particularly influenced by construction, while the agricultural sector, including forestry, and fisheries, represents 18.5%, and the manufacturing sector contributes a modest 6.3% to the economy.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] As of 2025, Albania's nominal gross domestic product (GDP) is reported at $26.911 billion with a GDP per capita of $9,474.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The projected annual percentage change in economic growth for 2025 is 3.8%, with a forecasted moderation to 3.5% by 2029.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Albania has developed a comprehensive framework for international trade through several pivotal agreements with various regions.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The Stabilisation and Association Agreement (SAA) with the European Union (EU), signed in 2006, is one of the most significant.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] This agreement provides critical trade benefits and serves as a foundation for the Albanian integration into the EU.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] In 2009, Albania signed a free trade agreement (FTA) with the European Free Trade Association (EFTA), which further expands trade opportunities and market access.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The country is also a signatory to the Central European Free Trade Agreement (CEFTA) and Organization of the Black Sea Economic Cooperation (BSEC), promoting regional trade and collaboration with neighboring countries.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Furthermore, the country has enhanced its bilateral trade relations through a FTA with Turkey, the United Kingdom and a bilateral investment treaty with the United States.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The 2023 Economic Freedom of the World report placed Albania in the 31st position, noting a considerable degree of economic independence and the effective adoption of market-oriented policies.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The 2024 Bertelsmann Transformation Index ranked Albania 20th and acknowledged substantial progress in political and economic transformation.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Also in 2024, the country was positioned 23rd in the Global Gender Gap Index, excelling in the Economic Participation and Opportunity category with a global ranking of 16th, showcasing significant advancements in women's economic participation.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] However, the Albanian economy, despite demonstrating considerable resilience, encounters substantial vulnerabilities that hinder its development.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Principal challenges include widespread corruption, distorted competition, and frequent modifications to fiscal legislation.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Furthermore, inadequate contract enforcement, a large informal sector, and persistent labor shortages further complicate the national economic progress.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Economic landscape of Albania is characterised by regional disparities, particularly apparent in the concentration of economic activities in the triangular region formed by Tirana, Durrës and Laç.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] This metropolitan area, referred to as Durana, functions as the principal economic center of Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] In the year 2021, Tirana County accounted for a significant 44% of the national GDP, with the counties of Fier and Durrës also playing integral roles in the economy, contributing 11% and 10% to the GDP, respectively.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Other substantial economic centers, such as Elbasan and the coastal cities of Sarandë and Vlorë, highlight the uneven distribution of economic development across the country.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Cultural regions, including Berat and Korçë, despite their geographical distance from the primary economic hubs, have derived considerable benefits from the expansion of the tourism sector.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Concerns over illicit finance, money laundering and organised-crime influence have become increasingly prominent in assessments of Albania's economy.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The United States Department of State has identified Albania as vulnerable to money laundering, with criminal proceeds laundered through real estate purchases, construction projects, virtual assets and business development.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Its 2025 Investment Climate Statement also described Albania's economic development as vulnerable because of widespread corruption, organised crime, distorted competition, labour shortages, low productivity and a large informal sector.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The Global Initiative Against Transnational Organized Crime's 2025 Global Organized Crime Index described Albania as a prominent destination for money laundering, stating that criminal organisations exploit the real estate, tourism and construction sectors to legitimise illicit profits.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] It also reported that the construction sector is heavily infiltrated by illicit funds, distorting the market, and that corruption within political and law-enforcement institutions continues to facilitate organised crime.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The government has generally rejected accusations of political protection for organised crime and has pointed to justice reform, anti-money-laundering measures and investigations by the Special Structure against Corruption and Organized Crime as evidence of progress.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Further, the country is a worldwide significant producer of salvia, rosemary and yellow gentian.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The country's proximity to the Ionian Sea and the Adriatic Sea give the underdeveloped fishing industry great potential.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The World Bank and European Community economists report that, Albania's fishing industry has good potential to generate export earnings because prices in the nearby Greek and Italian markets are many times higher than those in the Albanian market.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The fish available off the coasts of the country are carp, trout, sea bream, mussels and crustaceans.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Albania has one of Europe's longest histories of viticulture.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Today's region was one of the few places where vine was naturally grown during the ice age.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The oldest found seeds in the region are 4,000 to 6,000 years old.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] In 2009, the nation produced an estimated 17,500 tonnes of wine.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Albania's secondary sector has undergone many changes and diversification since the communist regime collapsed.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] It is very diversified, from electronics, manufacturing, textiles, to food, cement, mining, and energy.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The Antea Cement plant in Fushë-Krujë is considered one of the nation's largest industrial greenfield investments.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Albanian oil and gas is one of the most promising, albeit strictly regulated, sectors of its economy.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Albania has the second-largest oil deposits in the Balkan peninsula after Romania, and the largest oil reserves in Europe.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The Albpetrol company is owned by the Albanian state and monitors the state petroleum agreements in the country.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The textile industry has seen an extensive expansion by approaching companies from the European Union (EU) in Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] According to the Instituti i Statistikës (INSTAT), as of 2016, textile production had an annual growth of 5.3% and an annual turnover of around 1.5 billion euros.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Albania is a significant minerals producer and ranks among the world's leading chromium producers and exporters.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The nation is also a notable producer of copper, nickel, and coal.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The Batra mine, Bulqizë mine, and Thekna mine are among the most recognised Albanian mines still in operation.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The tertiary sector represents the fastest growing sector of the country's economy.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] 36% of the population work in the service sector which contributes to 65% of the country's GDP.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Ever since the end of the 20th century, the banking industry is a major component of the tertiary sector and remains in good conditions overall due to privatisation and the commendable monetary policy.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Previously one of the most isolated and controlled countries in the world, telecommunication industry represents nowadays another major contributor to the sector.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] It developed largely through privatisation and subsequent investment by both domestic and foreign investors.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Eagle, Vodafone and Telekom Albania are the leading telecommunications service providers in the country.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Tourism is recognised as an industry of national importance and has been steadily increasing since the beginnings of the 21st century.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] It directly accounted for 8.4% of GDP in 2016 though including indirect contributions pushes the proportion to 26%.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] In the same year, the country received approximately 4.74 million visitors mostly from across Europe and the United States as well.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The increase of foreign visitors has been dramatic.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Albania had only 500,000 visitors in 2005, and an estimated 4.2 million in 2012, an increase of 740 percent.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] According to the United Nations World Tourism Organization (UN Tourism), Albania welcomed approximately 11.7 million tourists in 2024, marking a significant increase from previous years.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The bulk of the tourist industry is concentrated along the Adriatic and Ionian Sea in the west of the country.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] But the Albanian Riviera in the southwest has the most scenic and pristine beaches; its coastline has a considerable length of 446 kilometres (277 miles).
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The coast has a distinctive character, rich in varieties of virgin beaches, capes, coves, covered bays, lagoons, small gravel beaches, sea caves, and many landforms.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Some parts of this seaside are very clean ecologically, including unexplored areas, which are very rare within the Mediterranean.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Other attractions include the mountainous areas such as the Albanian Alps, Ceraunian Mountains and Korab Mountains but also the historical cities of Berat, Durrës, Gjirokastër, Sarandë, Shkodër and Korçë.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The international airport of Tirana is the premier air gateway to the country, and is also the principal hub for Albania's national flag carrier airline, Air Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The airport carried more than 3.3 million passengers in 2019 with connections to many destinations in other countries around Europe, Africa and Asia.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The country plans to progressively increase the number of airports especially in the south with possible locations in Sarandë, Gjirokastër and Vlorë.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The highways and motorways in Albania are properly maintained and often still under construction and renovation.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The Autostrada 1 (A1) is an integral transportation corridor and the country's longest motorway.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] It is planned to link Durrës on the Adriatic Sea across Pristina in Kosovo with the Pan-European Corridor X in Serbia.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The Autostrada 2 (A2) is part of the Adriatic–Ionian Corridor as well as the Pan-European Corridor VIII and connects Fier with Vlorë.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The Autostrada 3 (A3) is under construction and after its completion will connect Tirana and Elbasan with the Pan-European Corridor VIII.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] When all three corridors are completed, Albania will have an estimated 759 kilometres (472 mi) of highway, linking it with all neighboring countries.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Durrës is the busiest and largest seaport in the country, followed by Vlorë, Shëngjin and Sarandë.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The rail network is administered by the national railway company Hekurudha Shqiptare.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] A new railway line from Tirana and its airport to Durrës is planned.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The location of this railway, connecting Albania's most populated urban areas, makes it an important economic development project.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Due to its location and natural resources, Albania has a wide variety of energy resources, ranging from gas, oil, and coal to wind, solar, water, and other renewable sources.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] According to the World Economic Forum's 2023 Energy Transition Index (ETI), the country ranked 21st globally, highlighting the progress in its energy transition agenda.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Currently, Albania's electricity generation sector depends on hydroelectricity, ranking fifth in the world in percentage terms.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Increasing risks of river floods and droughts due to climate change is expected to put electricity generation at risk.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The Drin, in the north, hosts four hydroelectric power stations, including Fierza, Koman, Skavica and Vau i Dejës.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Two other power stations, such as the Banjë and Moglicë, are along the Devoll in the south.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] It has the 10th-largest oil reserves in Europe and the 58th in the world.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The country's main petroleum deposits are located around the Albanian Adriatic Sea Coast and Myzeqe Plain within the Western Lowlands, where the country's largest reserve is located.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Patos-Marinza, also located within the area, is the largest onshore oil field in Europe.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The Trans Adriatic Pipeline (TAP), part of the planned Southern Gas Corridor, runs for 215 kilometres (134 miles) across Albania's territory before entering the Albanian Adriatic Sea Coast approximately 17 kilometres (11 miles) northwest of Fier.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Albania's water resources are particularly abundant in all the regions of the country and comprise lakes, rivers, springs, and groundwater aquifers.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The country's available average quantity of fresh water is estimated at 129.7 cubic metres (4,580 cubic feet) per inhabitant per year, one of the highest rates in Europe.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] According to data presented by the Joint Monitoring Programme for Water Supply and Sanitation (JMP) in 2015, about 93% of the country's total population had access to improved sanitation.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The freedom of press and freedom of speech, and the right to free expression are guaranteed by the Constitution of Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] In practice, however, media freedom has been weakened by political pressure, concentrated ownership, opaque financing, intimidation of journalists and the overlap between media, business and political interests.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Albania ranked 84th in the World Press Freedom Index of 2020 compiled by Reporters Without Borders.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Reporters Without Borders has continued to describe the Albanian media environment as fragile, stating that press freedom and media independence are threatened by conflicts of interest between business and politics, a flawed legal framework and partisan regulation.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] In 2026, Albania ranked 83rd of 180 countries in the World Press Freedom Index.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Radio Televizioni Shqiptar (RTSH) is the public broadcaster of Albania, operating television and radio stations throughout the country.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The main private broadcasters include Top Channel, TV Klan, Vizion Plus, A2 CNN, Syri TV and Ora News.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Albanian television content is also distributed in Kosovo and other Albanian-speaking territories.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Reporters Without Borders states that the most influential private-sector media are owned by a small number of companies with links to the political world and to highly regulated sectors such as construction.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The Media Freedom Rapid Response reported that the top four owners in the Albanian television market reach between 48.93% and 58.60% of audiences, and that the boundaries between media, politics and economics remain blurred.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] According to these assessments, media owners often use their outlets to protect business interests or influence governments and political parties, while state advertising and public funds are distributed in opaque ways that can create political dependence.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The media environment has become a central part of criticism of Prime Minister Edi Rama's long rule.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] International media-freedom organisations and Albanian journalists have accused the government of using communication centralisation, selective access, public-relations material and attacks on critical reporters to dominate the information space.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Reporters Without Borders has stated that journalists face political pressure, especially during elections, and that politicians limit editorial independence by politicising regulators and the public broadcaster.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The Media Freedom Rapid Response cited BIRN Albania editor Gjergj Erebara as saying that large parts of the Albanian media landscape operate under government propaganda and disinformation pressure.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Journalists who investigate corruption, organised crime or politically connected business interests face particular risks.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Reporters Without Borders states that journalists investigating crime and corruption are frequent targets of threats and that self-censorship is widespread.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] It also reports that critical journalists are subjected to discrediting attacks by both government and opposition politicians, while organised crime remains a major threat to journalists' safety.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] In March 2023, the headquarters of Top Channel was attacked with automatic weapons, killing a security guard.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The public broadcaster has also been part of the debate over media capture and political pressure.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] In 2026, international media-freedom organisations warned that democratic reform of RTSH should not be carried out through funding cuts, suspension or closure, arguing that such measures would violate European standards for public service media.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Albanian cinema has its roots in the 20th century and developed after the country's declaration of independence.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The first movie theater exclusively devoted to showing motion pictures was built in 1912 in Shkodër.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] During the People's Republic of Albania, Albanian cinema developed rapidly with the inauguration of the Kinostudio Shqipëria e Re in Tirana.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] In 1953, the Albanian-Soviet epic film *The Great Warrior Skanderbeg* was released, chronicling the life and fight of the medieval Albanian hero Skanderbeg.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] It went on to win an international prize at the 1954 Cannes Film Festival.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] In 2003, the Tirana International Film Festival was established, the largest film festival in the country.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The Durrës Amphitheatre hosts the Durrës International Film Festival, the country's second largest film festival.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] After the fall of communism in 1991, human resources in sciences and technology in Albania have drastically decreased.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] As of various reports, during 1991 to 2005 approximately 50% of the professors and scientists of the universities and science institutions in the country have left Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Albania was ranked 67th in the Global Innovation Index in 2025.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Telecommunication represents one of the fastest growing and dynamic sectors in Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Vodafone Albania, Telekom Albania and Albtelecom are the three large providers of mobile and internet in Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] As of the Electronic and Postal Communications Authority (AKEP) in 2018, the country had approximately 2.7 million active mobile users with almost 1.8 million active broadband subscribers.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Vodafone Albania alone served more than 931,000 mobile users, Telekom Albania had about 605,000 users and Albtelecom had more than 272,000 users.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] In January 2023, Albania launched its first two satellites, *Albania 1* and *Albania 2*, into orbit, in what was regarded as a milestone effort in monitoring the country's territory and identifying illegal activities.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Albanian-American engineer Mira Murati, the Chief Technology Officer of research organisation OpenAI, played a substantial role in the development and launch of artificial intelligence services such as ChatGPT, Codex and DALL-E.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] In December 2023, Prime Minister Edi Rama announced plans for collaboration between the Albanian government and ChatGPT, facilitated by discussions with Murati.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Rama emphasised the intention to streamline the alignment of Albanian laws with the regulations of the European Union, aiming to reduce costs associated with translation and legal services.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The demographic statistics of Albania, as revealed by the 2023 census conducted by the Instituti i Statistikave (INSTAT), indicated a population of 2,402,113, with a notable decline from the 2,821,977 recorded in the 2011 census.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The decrease in inhabitants began after the disintegration of the communist regime in Albania and is associated with significant shifts within the political, economic, and social structure of Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] A principal factor in this transition incorporates a decline in fertility rates coupled with an increase in emigration, both contributing to persistent demographic changes and challenges.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] It is forecast that the population will continue shrinking for the next decade at least, depending on the actual rates and the level of migration.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Currently, the population density of Albania is measured at 83.6 inhabitants per square kilometer with a varied distribution of inhabitants across different regions.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The counties of Tirana and Durrës showcase substantial concentrations of people, accounting for about 41% of the overall demographic of Albania, with 32% residing in Tirana and 9% in Durrës.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Conversely, more peripheral and rural counties such as Gjirokastër and Kukës present significantly lower population densities, with each aiding 3% to the overall population.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Historically, the Albanian people have established several communities in many regions throughout Southern Europe.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The Albanian diaspora has been formed since the late Middle Ages, when they emigrated to escape either various socio-political difficulties or the Ottoman conquest of Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Following the fall of communism, large numbers of Albanians have migrated to countries such as Australia, Canada, Switzerland, the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Albanian minorities are present in the neighbouring territories such as the west of North Macedonia, the southeast of Montenegro, Kosovo in its entirety and parts of southern Serbia.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Altogether, the number of ethnic Albanians living abroad is estimated to be higher than the total population inside Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] As much as a third of those born in the country's borders now live outside of it, making Albania one of the countries with the highest rate of outmigration relative to its population in the world.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] In 2022 the birth rate was 20% lower than in 2021, largely due to emigration of people of childbearing age.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Subsequent to the collapse of communism in 1991, Albania has undergone a remarkable transformation in its urban landscape, emerging as one of the fastest urbanising countries in Europe.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] At the forefront of this transformation is the Tirana–Durrës agglomeration, a densely populated urban corridor situated along the western coast of Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] This corridor has become the primary locus of population growth and settlement development, attracting a significant influx of internal migrants from the country's peripheral areas.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Despite an overall decline of the country's total population, the proportion of the urban demographic has consistently progressed from 47% in 2001 to 65% in 2023.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] This sustained increase, coupled with the concentration in the Tirana-Durrës region, has led to a spread of regional imbalances, with the peripheral areas, particularly Dibër and Kukës, experiencing severe depopulation.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The official language of the country is Albanian which is spoken by the vast majority of the country's population.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Its standard spoken and written form is revised and merged from the two main dialects, Gheg and Tosk, though it is notably based more on the Tosk dialect.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The Shkumbin river is the rough dividing line between the two dialects.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Among minority languages, Greek is the second most-spoken language in the country, with 0.5 to 3% of the population speaking it as first language, mainly in the country's south where its speakers are concentrated.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Other languages spoken by ethnic minorities in Albania include Aromanian, Serbo-Croatian, Macedonian, Bulgarian, Gorani, and Roma.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Macedonian is official in the Pustec Municipality in East Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] In the 2023 population census, 91.07% reported Albanian as the language spoken at home.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] 1.54% declared to speak at home another language, 0.57% multiple languages, 1.21% gave no answer and 5.59% were unavailable.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Among young people aged 25 or less, English, German and Turkish have seen rising interest after 2000.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Italian and French have had a stable interest, while Greek has lost much of its previous interest.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The trends are linked with cultural and economic factors.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] In the mid-2010s, an increasing number of Albanians showed interest in learning the German language, which has been explained as part of "a Western Balkan trend of preparing to integrate into the German labor market".
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Some of them have gone to Germany for studies or work.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Albania and Germany have agreements for cooperating in helping young people of the two countries know both cultures better.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Due to a sharp rise in economic relations with Turkey, interest in learning Turkish, in particular among young people, was also growing on a yearly basis in the 2010s.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Designated national and cultural minorities in Albania include Aromanian, Greek, Macedonian, Montenegrin, Serb, Roma, Egyptian, Bosnian and Bulgarian peoples, as well as Gorani and Jews as other minority groups.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Albania is a secular and religiously diverse country with no official religion.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Freedom of religion, belief and conscience are guaranteed under the country's constitution.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Albania is nevertheless ranked among the least religious countries in the world.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Religion constitute an important role in the lives of only 39% of the country's population.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] In another report, 56% considered themselves religious, 30% considered themselves non-religious, while 9% defined themselves as convinced atheists.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The Muslim Albanians are spread throughout the country.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Orthodox and Bektashis are mostly found in the south, whereas Catholics mainly live in the north.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] In 2008, there were 694 Catholic churches and 425 Orthodox churches, 568 mosques and 70 bektashi takyas in the country.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] During modern times, the Albanian republican, monarchic and later communist regimes followed a systematic policy of separating religion from official functions and cultural life.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The country has never had an official religion either as a republic or as a kingdom.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] In the 20th century, the clergy of all faiths was weakened under the monarchy and ultimately eradicated during the 1950s and 1960s, under the state policy of obliterating all organised religion from the territories of Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The communist regime persecuted and suppressed religious observance and institutions and entirely banned religion.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The country was then officially declared to be the world's first atheist state.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Religious freedom has returned, however, since the end of communism.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Islam survived communist era persecution and reemerged in the modern era as a practised religion in Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Some smaller Christian sects in Albania include Evangelicals and several Protestant communities including Seventh-day Adventist Church, Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints and Jehovah's Witnesses.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The first recorded Protestant of Albania was Said Toptani, who travelled around Europe and returned to Tirana in 1853, where he preached Protestantism.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The first evangelical Protestants appeared in the 19th century and the Evangelical Alliance was founded in 1892.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Nowadays, it has 160 member congregations from different Protestant denominations.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Following mass emigration to Israel after the fall of communism, there are only 200 Albanian Jews left in the country.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] In Albania, education is secular, free, compulsory, and based on three levels.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The academic year is apportioned into two semesters, beginning in September or October and ending in June or July.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Albanian is the primary language of instruction in the country's academic institutions.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The study of a first foreign language is mandatory and taught most often at elementary and bilingual schools.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Languages taught in schools are English, Italian, French and German.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Albania has a school life expectancy of 16 years and a literacy rate of 98.7%, with 99.2% for men and 98.3% for women.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Compulsory primary education is divided into two levels, elementary and secondary school, from grade one to five and six to nine, respectively.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Pupils are required to attend school from the age six until they turn 16.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Upon successful completion of primary education, all pupils are entitled to attend high schools, specialising in any field, including arts, sports, languages, sciences, and technology.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Tertiary education is optional and has undergone a thorough reformation and restructuring in compliance with the principles of the Bologna Process.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] There are a significant number of private and public institutions of higher education in Albania's major cities.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Tertiary education is organised into three successive levels, the bachelor, master, and doctorate.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The constitution of Albania guarantees its citizens equal, free, and universal health care.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The health care system is organised into primary, secondary, and tertiary healthcare, and is in a process of modernisation and development.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The life expectancy at birth in Albania is 77.8 years, ranking 37th in the world and surpassing several developed countries.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The average healthy life expectancy is 68.8 years, ranking 37th in the world.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] The country's infant mortality rate was estimated at 12 per 1,000 live births in 2015.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] In 2000, the country had the world's 55th-best healthcare performance, as defined by the World Health Organisation (WHO).
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Cardiovascular disease is the principal cause of death in Albania, accounting for 52% of deaths.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Accidents, injuries, malignant and respiratory diseases are other primary causes of death.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Neuropsychiatric disease has also increased due to recent demographic, social, and economic changes in the country.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] In 2009, Albania had a fruit and vegetable supply of 886 grams per capita per day, the fifth-highest supply in Europe.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] Compared to other developed and developing countries, Albania has a relatively low rate of obesity, probably thanks to the Mediterranean diet.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p03] According to 2016 WHO data, 21.7% of adults in the country are clinically overweight, with a Body mass index (BMI) score of 25 or more.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] The red and black national colours are displayed on the flag of Albania that is adorned with a double-headed eagle as the foremost recognised national symbol of Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] With the black eagle portraying bravery and strength, the red field symbolises the fortitude and sacrifices of the Albanian people.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] The eagle is linked with the legacy of the national hero Gjergj Kastrioti, renowned as Skanderbeg, who led a prosperous resistance movement against Ottoman rule.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Rooted in the Middle Ages, it emerged as a heraldic symbol in the Principality of Arbër and among notable Albanian dynasties such as the Dukagjini, Kastrioti, Muzaka and Thopia clans.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Amid the Albanian Renaissance, marking the resurgence of Albanian national identity and aspirations for independence, the Albanian eagle regained its prominence.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Its importance reached its culmination with Albania's declaration of independence in 1912, when Ismail Qemali raised it as the national flag in Vlorë.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] The coat of arms of Albania is an adaptation of the flag of Albania and the seal of Skanderbeg.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] The coat comprises the black double-headed eagle positioned at the centre of a red field.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Above the eagle, it carries the helmet of Skanderbeg that is crowned with the head of a golden horned goat.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Ti Shqipëri, më jep nder, më jep emrin Shqipëtar, which translates to "You Albania, give me honour, give me the name Albanian", is the national motto of Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] It finds its foundation in the legacy of national poet Naim Frashëri, who held a renowned role during the Albanian Renaissance.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] The national anthem of Albania, "Himni i Flamurit", was composed by Asdreni and adopted as such following Albania's independence in 1912.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Albanian traditional clothing, with its contrasting variations for the northern Gheg and southern Tosk Albanians, is a testament to Albania's history, cultural diversity and ethnic identity.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Gheg men wear a light-colored shirt paired with wide loose-fitting trousers referred to as the Tirq.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] These trousers are securely fastened by a wide woven belt, the Brez.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] An integral component of their costume is the Xhamadan, a woolen red velvet vest adorned with folkloric motifs and gold patterns.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] They also wear a distinctive dome-shaped hat known as the Qeleshe, crafted from wool, with its origins tracing back to the Illyrians.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Conversely, Tosk men opt for the Fustanella, a knee-length garment designated as the national costume, typically white with pleats, accompanied by a white shirt.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] They also wear a beige or dark blue Xhamadan reminiscent of the Gheg attire.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] To complete their attire, men wear knee-high socks referred to as Çorape and leather shoes known as Opinga.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] The attire of Gheg and Tosk women is renowned for its rich palette of colors and intricate filigree detailing, displayed across various components including ear ornaments, finger rings, necklaces, belt buckles and buttons.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Key components include a long, light-toned shirt paired with an apron, often accompanied by a woolen or felt mantle referred to as the Xhoka.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Additional upper garments, such as the Dollama or Mintan, may be layered, along with a headscarf known as Kapica or Shall.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] A distinctive variation incorporates a pair of aprons, including the Pështjellak at the rear and the Paranik at the front.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Integral to the traditional attire of Gheg women is the ancient Xhubleta.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Dedicated efforts have been undertaken to preserve and promote the dress, acknowledging its significance as an emblem of Albanian heritage.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] As a testament to its importance, the Xhubleta has been inscribed on the UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage List.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] The distinctive bell-shaped garment is fashioned in black and enriched with embroidered ethnic Albanian motifs, showcasing the remarkable craftsmanship of northern Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Its crafting process involves multiple intricate stages, encompassing the preparation of shajak fabric and the precise cutting techniques.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] The artistic history of Albania has been particularly influenced by a multitude of ancient and medieval people, traditions and religions.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] It covers a broad spectrum with mediums and disciplines that include painting, pottery, sculpture, ceramics and architecture all of them exemplifying a great variety in style and shape, in different regions and period.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] The rise of the Byzantine and Ottoman Empire in the Middle Ages was accompanied by a corresponding growth in Christian and Islamic art in the lands of Albania which are apparent in examples of architecture and mosaics throughout the country.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Centuries later, the Albanian Renaissance proved crucial to the emancipation of the modern Albanian culture and saw unprecedented developments in all fields of literature and art whereas artists sought to return to the ideals of Impressionism and Romanticism.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] However, Onufri, Kolë Idromeno, David Selenica, Kostandin Shpataraku and the Zografi Brothers are the most eminent representatives of Albanian art.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] The architecture of Albania reflects the legacy of various civilisations tracing back to the classical antiquity.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Major cities in Albania have evolved from within the castle to include dwellings, religious and commercial structures, with constant redesigning of town squares and evolution of building techniques.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Nowadays, the cities and towns reflect a whole spectrum of various architectural styles.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] In the 20th century, many historical as well as sacred buildings bearing the ancient influence were demolished during the communist era.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Ancient architecture is found throughout Albania and most visible in Byllis, Amantia, Phoenice, Apollonia, Butrint, Antigonia, Shkodër and Durrës.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Considering the long period of rule of the Byzantine Empire, they introduced castles, citadels, churches and monasteries with spectacular wealth of visible murals and frescos.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Perhaps the best known examples can be found in the southern Albanian cities and surroundings of Korçë, Berat, Voskopojë and Gjirokastër.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Involving the introduction of Ottoman architecture there was a development of mosques and other Islamic buildings, particularly seen in Berat and Gjirokastër.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] A productive period of Historicism, Art Nouveau and Neoclassicism merged into the 19th century, best exemplified in Korçë.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] The 20th century brought new architectural styles such as the modern Italian style, which is present in Tirana such as the Skanderbeg Square and Ministries.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] It is also present in Shkodër, Vlorë, Sarandë and Durrës.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Moreover, other towns received their present-day Albania-unique appearance through various cultural or economic influences.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Socialist classicism arrived during the communist era in Albania after the Second World War.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] At this period many socialist-styled complexes, wide roads and factories were constructed, while town squares were redesigned and numerous of historic and important buildings demolished.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Notable examples of that style include the Mother Teresa Square, Pyramid of Tirana, Palace of Congresses and so on.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Three Albanian archaeological sites are included in the list of UNESCO World Heritage Sites.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] These include the ancient remains of Butrint, the medieval Historic Centres of Berat and Gjirokastër, and Natural and Cultural Heritage of the Ohrid region site shared with North Macedonia since 2019.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Furthermore, the royal Illyrian tombs, the remains of Apollonia, the ancient Amphitheatre of Durrës and the Fortress of Bashtovë has been included on the tentative list of Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Albanian folk music is a prominent part of the national identity, and continues to play a major part in overall Albanian music.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Folk music can be divided into two stylistic groups, mainly the northern Gheg varieties, and southern Lab and Tosk varieties.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Northern and southern traditions are contrasted by a rugged tone from the north, and the more relaxed southern form of music.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Many songs concern events from Albanian history and culture, including traditional themes of honour, hospitality, treachery, and revenge.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] The first compilation of Albanian folk music was made by two Himariot musicians, Neço Muka and Koço Çakali, in Paris, during their work with Albanian soprano Tefta Tashko-Koço.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Several gramophone compilations were recorded at the time by the three artists, which eventually led to the recognition of Albanian iso-polyphony as a UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Festivali i Këngës is a traditional Albanian song contest organised by the national broadcaster Radio Televizioni Shqiptar (RTSH).
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] The festival is celebrated annually since its inauguration in 1962 and has launched the careers of some of Albania's most successful singers including Vaçe Zela and Parashqevi Simaku.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] It is significantly a music competition among Albanian performers presenting unreleased songs in premiere, composed by Albanian authors and voted by juries or by public.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Contemporary artists Rita Ora, Bebe Rexha, Era Istrefi, Dua Lipa, Ava Max, Bleona, Elvana Gjata, Ermonela Jaho, and Inva Mula have achieved international recognition for their music, while soprano Ermonela Jaho has been described by some as the "world's most acclaimed soprano".
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Albanian opera singer Saimir Pirgu was nominated for the 2017 Grammy Award.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] The cultural renaissance was first of all expressed through the development of the Albanian language in the area of church texts and publications.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] The Protestant reforms invigorated hopes for the development of the local language and literary tradition, when cleric Gjon Buzuku translated the Catholic liturgy into Albanian, trying to do for Albanian what Martin Luther had done for German.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Meshari (*The Missal*) written by Gjon Buzuku was published in 1555 and is considered one of the first literary work of written Albanian during the Middle Ages.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] The refined level of the language and the stabilised orthography must be the result of an earlier tradition of written Albanian, a tradition that is not well understood.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] However, there is some fragmented evidence, pre-dating Buzuku, which indicates that Albanian was written from at least the 14th century.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Albanian writings from these centuries must not have been religious texts only, but historical chronicles too.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] The *History of Skanderbeg* is still the foundation of Skanderbeg studies and is considered an Albanian cultural treasure, vital to the formation of Albanian national self-consciousness.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] The most famous Albanian writer in the 20th and 21st century is probably Ismail Kadare.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Throughout the centuries, Albanian cuisine has been widely influenced by Albanian culture, geography and history, and as such, different parts of the country enjoy specific regional cuisines.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Cooking traditions especially vary between the north and the south, owing to differing topography and climate that essentially contribute to the excellent growth conditions for a wide array of herbs, fruits, and vegetables.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Albanians produce and use many varieties of fruits such as lemons, oranges, figs, and most notably, olives, which are perhaps the most important element of Albanian cooking.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Spices and other herbs such as basil, lavender, mint, oregano, rosemary, and thyme are widely used, as are vegetables such as garlic, onions, peppers, potatoes, tomatoes, as well as legumes of all types.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] With a coastline along the Adriatic and Ionian in the Mediterranean Sea, fish, crustaceans, and seafood are a popular and an integral part of the Albanian diet.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Otherwise, lamb is the traditional meat for different holidays and religious festivals for both Christians and Muslims, although poultry, beef, and pork are also in plentiful supply.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Tavë kosi ("soured milk casserole") is the national dish of Albania, consisting of lamb and rice baked under a thick, tart veil of yoghurt.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Fërgesë is another national dish, made up of peppers, tomatoes, and cottage cheese.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Pite is also popular, a baked pastry with a filling of a mixture of spinach and gjizë (curd) or mish (ground meat).
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Petulla, a traditional fried dough, is also a popular speciality, and is served with powdered sugar or feta cheese and different sorts of fruit jams.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Flia consists of multiple crêpe-like layers brushed with cream and served with sour cream.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Krofne, similar to Berliner doughnuts, are filled with jam, or chocolate and often eaten during winter.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Coffee is an integral part of the Albanian lifestyle.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] The country has more coffee houses per capita than any other country in the world.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Tea is also enjoyed both at home or outside at cafés, bars, or restaurants. Çaj Mali (Sideritis tea) is enormously beloved, and a part of the daily routine for most Albanians.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] It is cultivated across Southern Albania and noted for its medicinal properties.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Albanian wine is also common throughout the country, and has been cultivated for thousands of years.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Albania has a long and ancient history of wine production, and belongs to the Old World of wine producing countries.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Albania participated at the Olympic Games in 1972 for the first time.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] The country made their Winter Olympic Games debut in 2006.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Albania missed the next four games, two of them due to the 1980 and 1984 boycotts, but returned for the 1992 games in Barcelona.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Since then, Albania have participated in all games.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Albania normally competes in events that include swimming, athletics, weightlifting, shooting and wrestling.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] The country have been represented by the National Olympic Committee of Albania since 1972.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] The nation has participated at the Mediterranean Games since the games of 1987 in Syria.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] The Albanian athletes have won a total of 43 (8 gold, 17 silver and 18 bronze) medals from 1987 to 2013.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Popular sports in Albania include football, weightlifting, basketball, volleyball, tennis, swimming, rugby union and gymnastics.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Football is by far the most popular sport in Albania.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] It is governed by the Football Association of Albania (Albanian: *Federata Shqiptare e Futbollit*, F.SH.F.), which has membership in FIFA and UEFA.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Albania scored their first ever goal in a major tournament and secured their first ever win in European Championship when they beat Romania by 1–0 in a UEFA Euro 2016 match on 19 June 2016.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] The most successful football clubs are Skënderbeu, KF Tirana, Dinamo Tirana, Partizani and Vllaznia.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Weightlifting is one of the most successful individual sports for the Albanians, with the national team winning medals at the European Weightlifting Championships and the rest international competitions.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] Albanian weightlifters have won a total of 16 medals at the European Championships with one of them being gold, seven silver and eight bronze.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/albania-p04] In the World Weightlifting Championships, the Albanian weightlifting team has won in 1972 a gold, in 2002 a silver, and in 2011 a bronze medal.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] AM General has also been a provider of vehicles for the CUCV program carried out by the United States Armed Forces.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] AM General traces its roots to the Standard Wheel Company of Terre Haute, Indiana, which expanded in 1903 to include the Overland Automotive Division.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] In 1908, John North Willys purchased the Overland company, then based in Indianapolis, Indiana, and renamed it Willys-Overland Motors.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] Army awarded a contract to Willys-Overland Motor Company to produce the Willys MB, also known as the Jeep, for the U.S.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] It then mass-produced that vehicle as "America's first four-wheel-drive, one-fourth-ton, tactical utility truck"—the Jeep of World War II fame.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] In 1953, Kaiser Motors purchased Willys-Overland, changing its name first to Kaiser-Willys Motor Company, and in 1963, to Kaiser-Jeep Corporation.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] In 1970, it was purchased by American Motors Corporation (AMC).
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] In July 2020, KPS Capital Partners acquired the company.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] In 1964, Kaiser-Jeep purchased the Studebaker facilities on Chippewa Avenue in South Bend, Indiana, Studebaker's "General Products Division", and its substantial defense contracts.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] At the time, Kaiser had been awarded a US$87 million Army truck contract, and under government pressure, agreed to perform the work at the South Bend plant it had recently acquired from Studebaker.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] In 1970, American Motors Corporation (AMC) purchased the Jeep Corporation from Kaiser, when Kaiser decided to leave the auto business.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] In 1971, AMC made the General Products Division of Jeep (producing military trucks as well as contract and non-commercial vehicles) a wholly owned subsidiary and renamed it "AM General Corporation".
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] In 1982, American Motors ceased to function as an independent automaker when Renault purchased a total 46.1% interest.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] Federal government regulations at that time forbade ownership of defense contractors by foreign governments — and the French government partially owned Renault.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] In 1983, LTV Corporation bought AM General and established it as a wholly owned subsidiary.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] In 1984, its headquarters moved from the American Motors AMTEK Building in Detroit, Michigan, to Livonia, Michigan, and two years later to South Bend, Indiana, where primary manufacturing operations were located.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] In 1992, AM General was sold to Renco Group, which in 2002 converted it to a limited liability company.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] In 1984, AM General built a factory for HMMWV production at 13200 McKinley Hwy in Mishawaka.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] In 1992, AM General began marketing the HMMWV to the civilian market under the Hummer brand.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] In 1999, GM acquired the rights to the brand and continued production of the original civilian Hummer as the H1 until June 2006.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] In 2002, the Hummer H2 went on the market and was produced until January 2009.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] It was designed and marketed by GM, and manufactured by AM General at the Mishawaka plant.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] GM was sued early in 2003 by DaimlerChrysler, owners of the Jeep brand, for the resemblance of the Hummer's seven-slot grille to Jeep's.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] The lawsuit was dismissed after acknowledgment of the shared corporate history of AMC and Jeep.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] General Motors in turn sued boutique automaker Avanti Motor Corporation of Cancun, Mexico after it introduced the Studebaker XUV at the Chicago Auto show in 2002.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] General Motors said Avanti infringed on Hummer's look by planning a vehicle resembling the Hummer.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] The AM General Hummer line had returned to the original Studebaker General Products Division, responsible for all military contracts.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] In August 2004, it was announced that Ronald Perelman's MacAndrews & Forbes company would form a joint venture with AM General's then-owner, Renco Group, to give Perelman 70% ownership.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] The deal reportedly cost close to US$1 billion.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] In 2008, AM General and the Vehicle Production Group (VPG), of Troy, Michigan, announced that contracts had been signed for AM General to begin producing purpose-built taxi-cabs in 2009.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] The first vehicle off the line was presented to Marc Buoniconti, a former linebacker for The Citadel who was partially paralyzed in 1985.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] In May 2010, Azure Dynamics announced it had chosen AM General to assemble its electric drivetrain for Ford Transit Connect vehicles for the North American market at its Livonia, Michigan, factory.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] In September 2013, AM General reached an agreement to purchase the United States Department of Energy's secured loan to the Vehicle Production Group (VPG).
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] Prior to this, AM General acted as the sole vehicle assembler for VPG.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] As a result of this transaction, AM General created a wholly owned company, Mobility Ventures LLC, to operate the Mobility Vehicle-1 (MV-1) business and receive all VPG assets.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] In 2015, production of the Mercedes-Benz R-Class began at the Mishawaka assembly plant.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] Without this deal, "the German automaker would likely have had to shut down production of the vehicle, currently only sold in China." Production ended in October 2017.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] In July 2020, investment company KPS Capital Partners acquired AM General from its previous owner, MacAndrews & Forbes.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] AM General submitted a prototype to become the United States Postal Service's Next Generation Delivery Vehicle, but their entry was not chosen.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] The Jeep DJ-5 series was a purpose-built "Dispatch Jeep" two-wheel drive (RWD) version of the Jeep CJ-5.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] They became widely used by the United States Postal Service during the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] Although featuring an automatic transmission, they were rudimentary and built with a lighter, less durable design than the standard Jeep models.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] The USPS specified right-hand drive to reach mailboxes without leaving the vehicle's seat, an enclosed metal cabin with sliding sided doors, open rear cargo area, and a single seat with a sorting table on the left side for carriers to help process mail along their routes.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] The AM General Metropolitan buses were manufactured for city transit use from 1974 until 1979, producing a total of 5,431 buses, including 219 electric trolley buses.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] The Metropolitan was built under a 1971 agreement with Flyer Industries of Winnipeg, Manitoba.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] AM General licensed the rights to build and market the Western Flyer D700 for the U.S. market.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] The D700 itself was similar in design to the contemporaneous GM New Look buses.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] The front end of the D700 was restyled, and thus the resulting Metropolitan was not simply a Flyer design built under license but rather a jointly designed vehicle.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] Flyer later adopted the design changes for its own line as the models D800 and E800.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] The model numbers reflected the chosen dimensions.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] For example, model "10240" indicated a 102-inch wide, 40-foot long bus.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] Suffixes "A" or "B" were used for later models to indicate certain options.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] In total, 3,571 40-foot diesel buses and 1,641 35-foot diesel buses were produced.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] In 1977–1979, AM General worked under a partnership with MAN of Germany to build SG 220 articulated buses for U.S. transit systems.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] MAN fabricated the bodyshells in Germany and shipped them to the U.S. for AM General for final assembly.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] Two different lengths were offered, 55 ft (16.8 m) and 60 ft (18.3 m).
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] 93 buses were built to the shorter length and the rest were 60 feet long.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] In October 1978, the company discontinued bus production, with the last unit completed in March 1979.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] The total number built was just under 400 (392 or 399), the largest group being 150 for Seattle's Metro Transit.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] MAN subsequently set up its own factory for U.S. production in Cleveland, North Carolina.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] Production of complete motor buses (and of any two-axle motor buses) ended in 1978.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] Aside from the fitting-out of the last articulated MAN shells, the only production in 1979 was two batches of trolleybuses, the only such vehicles ever built by the company.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] These were all 40-foot (12.2 m) vehicles, model 10240T: 110 trackless trolleys for the Philadelphia trolleybus system, operated by SEPTA, and 109 for the Seattle trolleybus system, operated by Metro Transit, now King County Metro.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] One of the latter has been preserved since its retirement in 2003 by King County Metro (see King County Metro fleet).
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] In 1979, AM General began preliminary design work on the M998 Series High Mobility Multi-Purpose Wheeled Vehicle HMMWV, pronounced Humvee, a 1.25-ton truck intended to replace the M151 and other Light Utility Vehicles.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] Army awarded AM General a prototype contract.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] In 1982, development and operational testing was conducted over a five-month period.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] In March 1983, AM General won an initial $1.2 billion contract to produce 55,000 Humvees, to be delivered in five basic models and 15 different configurations over a five-year period.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] In the fall of 1984, production began at the Mishawaka, Indiana, assembly plant.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] In early 1985, the first deliveries were made.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] The total international production by mid-1991 was more than 72,000.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] After 1991, an additional 20,000 HMMWVs ordered brought total international production to 100,000 in March 1995.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] Late in 2000, AM General was awarded another contract for 2,962 M998A2 series trucks.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] The contract contained six single-year options running to the fiscal year 2007 and continues to be renewed.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] Nearly 250,000 units have been produced.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] Humvees feature full-time four-wheel drive, an independent suspension, steep approach and departure angles, 60-percent grade ability and 16 inches (406 mm) of ground clearance.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] More recent production models include the M1151, M1152, M1165, and M1167.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] As of 2015, Humvees are in use by the U.S.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] Army, Marine Corps, Air Force, and Navy.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] More than 50 nations have bought these vehicles.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] The Humvee's replacement, a completely new Joint Light Tactical Vehicle (JLTV) design, has been in production by Oshkosh Corporation since 2016.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] AM General was unsuccessful in its bid for this $30-billion 25-year contract, and it is now focused on military Humvee support (they still outnumber JLTVs by three to one) and development of a new ambulance model.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] Army granted AM General a production contract worth more than $8.66bn to deliver next-generation JLTV A2 vehicles, under the Army and Marine Corps’ Joint Light Tactical Vehicle (JLTV) program.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] Under the contract, AM General will produce approximately 20,682 JLTV vehicles and 9,883 trailers.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] The contract includes the integration of technological enhancements for delivery to the U.S.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] Oshkosh Defense won the initial contract to supply its JLTV vehicles for the program.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] AM General plans to participate in the Mobile Tactical Cannon (MTC) programme of the U.S.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] They are collaborating with India's Kalyani Strategic Systems Limited (KSSL), a subsidiary of Bharat Forge, which has developed the Mounted Artillery Gun MArG-52.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] By February 2025, KSSL and AM General signed a letter of intent for the supply of artillery cannons to support the latter's development of a range of 105 mm and 155 mm calibre next-generation artillery guns.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] On 18 June 2026, they signed a strategic partnership the Eurosatory defense exposition.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] The MArG-52 platform is claimed to be combat-relevant and a delivery is planned by 2027 once chosen.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] The system will be integrated with the patented Soft Recoil Technology (SRT) Recoil Mitigation system, an automated load-assist, and an all-weather fire-control suite providing indirect and direct fire capabilities.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] It fires a standard high-explosive ammunition at a maximum range of up to 40 km (25 mi) and has a capacity to carry 20 rounds and propellant charges on-board.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] AM General also acquired Department of Defense contracts for medium and heavy trucks, including the M151 series, 2 1/2 ton M35 series, and 5 ton M809 series in the 1970s, then the M939 series in the 1980s.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/am-general] In 2005, AM General was contracted to take over militarization, sales, and marketing of LSSV vehicles.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] The **Commercial Utility Cargo Vehicle** (**CUCV**; /ˈkʌkviː/ *KUK-vee*), later the **Light Service Support Vehicle** (**LSSV**), is a vehicle program instituted to provide the United States military with light utility vehicles based on a civilian truck chassis.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] Some of the manufacturers that have provided vehicles to the U.S. military are Chrysler, General Motors (through their Dodge and Chevrolet divisions respectively), and AM General.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] The Commercial Off The Shelf (COTS) concept, which translated into the CUCV program, was originally intended to augment the purpose-built but expensive Gama Goat 6 x 6, 1+1⁄4-ton trucks and M151 series 1⁄4-ton "jeeps" approaching the end of their service life in the mid-1970s.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] Initially, Dodge D series trucks were provided in the late 1970s with several military modifications.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] In the mid-1980s, Chevrolet C/Ks replaced the Dodge vehicles in CUCV I and CUCV II guise.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] GM CUCVs were heavily redesigned in 2000 and their name was changed to Light Service Support Vehicle (LSSV).
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] CUCVs are intended to perform "background" roles, providing support for frontline forces, such as cargo transport, troop transport, first aid, and communications.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] CUCVs are not built for direct frontline combat use, as evident by their lack of bulletproofing and protection from ordnance.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] Like many of the vehicle parts, the windshield, cabin glass, and body panels are civilian-grade and offer no protection from firearms or explosives.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] As a result, some CUCVs were replaced in the 1980s and 1990s by the HMMWVs they were to augment.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] The U.S. military continued to keep CUCVs in active service long after their projected lifespan.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] CUCVs of all generations are still in U.S. service, though many M880/M890s and CUCVs have passed through military surplus sales into civilian ownership.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] CUCVs and LSSVs are in use as support vehicles for military police, troop transport, range control, facilities, and maintenance.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] In 1973 Chrysler Corporation began developing militarized adaptations of their civilian Dodge trucks.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] In 1976 the M880/M890 series was put into production under a large contract, intended to replace previous Dodge M37 and Kaiser Jeep M715 trucks and their variants.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] The M880/890 trucks were adopted as part of a drive by the U.S. military to use COTS vehicles, with appropriate modifications, where such usage was feasible.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] An armored variant was built by Cadillac Gage as the Ranger.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] For almost a decade the Dodges were referred to as "880", "890", or most commonly called "five-quarters"; (the term "CUCV" did not appear until the 1980s when GM was contracted to replace the M880/890 trucks).
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] The 1+1⁄4 ton M880-series was based on the Dodge W200, a 3⁄4 ton capacity 4×4 civilian/commercial truck.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] The 880/890 had a 2,500 lb cargo rating, enabling it to have a 5⁄4-ton load rating.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] The similar 1+1⁄4 ton M890-series was based on the Dodge D200, a 3⁄4 ton capacity 4×2 civilian/commercial truck.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] In Canadian service, the base vehicle was the 4-speed standard transmission, Power Wagon model, which was slightly heavier and costlier than the W200.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] The M880/M890 had a conventional 12-volt electrical system; a separate 24-volt system was added to certain variants of the trucks to power communications units, but this precluded power steering on those units—the pump location being taken up by the 24-volt generator.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] The gasoline engine was out of step with the military's move toward diesel engines during this time period.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] The lack of power steering was a hindrance in off-road, close quarters, and snow-plowing duties (although most civilian and Air Force models had power steering).
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] Around 44,000 M880/M890s were produced during the 1976–1977 model years and were used by the Army and Air Force until the late 1990s.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] All M880/M890s were powered by Chrysler's 5.2 L 318-cubic inch gasoline engine with a two-barrel Carter or Holley carburetor.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] Most were equipped with the Loadflite 727 3-speed automatic transmission.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] The 880s used a 2-speed New Process Gear NP203 transfer case.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] A Dana 44 4.10:1 front axle and floating Dana 60 4:10.1 rear axle completed the setup.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] The trucks were equipped with front disc brakes and rear drum brakes.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] They had a military-rated top speed of 70 mph (110 km/h).
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] General Motors and AM General have produced CUCVs since 1984 in three distinct generations: CUCV, CUCV II, and LSSV.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] Replacing the M880/M890 series, the CUCV represented General Motors' first major light-truck military vehicle production since World War II.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] GM CUCVs were assembled mostly from existing heavy duty light commercial truck parts.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] The CUCVs came in four basic body styles: pickup, utility, ambulance body and chassis cab.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] The M1008 was the basic cargo truck, the M1010 was the ambulance, and the M1009 was a Chevrolet K5 Blazer uprated to 3⁄4-ton capacity.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] With the exception of the M1009, the trucks were all rated as 11⁄4 ton (commonly called a "five-quarter"), even though some of them had payloads in excess of that.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] There were heavier-duty variants, including the M1028, M1028A1, M1028A2 and M1028A3 shelter carriers (the shelter being a mobile command, communications or intelligence operations enclosure).
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] These latter trucks were all rated for heavier 3,600 lb (1,600 kg) or 3,900 lb (1,800 kg) loads, compared to the M1008s 2,900 lb (1,300 kg) load capacity.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] Many M1028s were upgraded at the company level to M1028A2 and A3 specs—the dual wheel rear end arrangement was a result of the M1028 flipping on its side because of the high center of gravity when carrying equipment shelters.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] GM produced some 70,000 CUCVs from 1983 to 1986 (model years were 1984–1987), though most were model year 1984.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] Chevrolet continued to build CUCVs in low numbers from 1986 to 1996, mainly to accommodate military markets that needed replacements for existing CUCVs.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] All CUCV Is were powered by GM's 6.2 L J-series Detroit Diesel V8 engine non-emissions diesel.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] These were rated at 155 hp (116 kW) and 240 lb⋅ft (325 N⋅m), which was 5 hp (3.7 kW) more than the emissions diesel engine of the time.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] They were all equipped with the TH-400 automatic.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] All but the M1028A1 and M1031 used the NP-208 chain drive transfer case.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] The M1028A1 and M1031 units had a slip-yoke rear output version of the NP-205, which was specified mainly for its PTO capacity.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] The CUCV series had a governed top speed of 55 mph (89 km/h).
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] The M1009 Blazer used 10-bolt axles (front and rear) featuring 3.08:1 gears.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] The rear axle was equipped with an *Eaton Automatic Differential Lock* (ADL) while the front was a standard open differential.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] The M1008 trucks used open Dana 60 front axles, with the M1028 and M1031 variations often having a Trac-Lok limited slip.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] In the rear, the M1008s used the GM 10.5-inch (270 mm) 10.5" Corporate 14 Bolt Differential with No-Spin lockers (the commercial trade name for the Detroit Locker).
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] Rear axles on M1028A2 and A3 duallies are Dana 70 HD.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] As with other military vehicles, the CUCVs used a 24-volt electrical system.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] It was actually a hybrid 12/24-volt system that used 24-volts under the hood for the starter, volt meter, diesel engine glow plug circuit along with the mandatory NATO slave receptacle for jump starting any 24 volt NATO vehicle, and hookups for military radios.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] It was equipped with two 12 volt batteries and two 12 volt 100 amp alternators.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] One alternator is isolated from ground and connected in series with the other.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] These produce 24 volts with a 12 volt center tap much like the 240/120 volt domestic house distribution system.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] The 12 volts to ground were derived from the center tap.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] In 1987, GM started building a new generation of CUCV.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] The US Air Force initially bought small batches of these units, dubbed the CUCV II.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] Produced through 2001, CUCV IIs were basic civilian Chevrolet C/K, Tahoe, and Suburban units sent to another plant for "militarization" on special order.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] The trucks were originally white in color with gray vinyl interiors.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] They received CARC exterior paint (Forest Green, Desert Sand, or 3-color camouflage), a brush bar, a pintle hitch, towing/loading shackles, extra leaf springs to give them a 5/4 ton rating and a host of other small changes.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] All CUCV IIs have a 24 volt dual-battery starting system, the rest of the truck is 12 volt.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] These light utility vehicles were available with three engines: a Vortec 7.4-liter V8, a 5.7-liter V8, or Detroit Diesel 6.5 L V8.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] Each engine was coupled with a 4-speed automatic or 5-speed manual transmission.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] All CUCV IIs have full-time all-wheel drive; a front-mounted winch was available as an option.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] When production of the CUCV II ended in 2000, GM redesigned it to coincide with civilian truck offerings.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] The CUCV nomenclature was changed to Light Service Support Vehicle (LSSV) in 2001.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] In 2005, LSSV production switched to AM General, a unit of MacAndrews and Forbes Holdings.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] The LSSV is a GM-built Chevrolet Silverado 1500, Chevrolet Silverado 2500 HD, Chevrolet Tahoe, or Chevrolet Suburban that is powered by a Duramax 6.6 liter turbo diesel engine.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] As GM has periodically redesigned its civilian trucks and sport utility vehicles (SUVs) from 2001 to the present, LSSVs have also been updated cosmetically.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] The dashboard has additional controls and dataplates.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] The truck also can be equipped with weapon supports in the cab, cargo tie down hooks, folding troop seats, pioneer tools, winches, and other military accessories.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] In the Canadian Army these vehicles are nicknamed "Milverado," a portmanteau for Military Silverado, "Milcot" for military commercial off-the-shelf and "Love W" short for LUVW.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] The Enhanced Mobility Package (EMP) option adds an uprated suspension, 4-wheel anti-lock brakes, a locking rear differential, beadlock tires, a Tire Pressure Monitoring System (TPMS) and other upgrades.
[src:commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle/commercial-utility-cargo-vehicle] About 2,000 LSSV units have been sold to U.S. and international military and law enforcement organizations.
